<HEAD>Carnegie Hall Recreates 1912 Concert</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The week in music here has been busy. The Mostly Mozart Festival kicked off in <ORGANIZATION> Lincoln </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, to run until Aug. 26. <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> inaugurated a large, new outdoor concert series on a <LOCATION> Hudson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> pier. And among the top musical delights was Friday night's recreation of a May 2, 1912, Clef Club Concert when <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Reese </PERSON> <PERSON> Europe </PERSON> brought 125 black singers and instrumentalists to Carnegie Hall. They performed music mostly by black composers, mostly high-quality, high-spirited light classical, no spirituals. It was a first for an American stage. High points of the evening included <PERSON> Jester </PERSON> <PERSON> Hairston </PERSON>, born in 1901, vigorously conducting `` Swing Along for Choir and Orchestra'' and `` Rain Song for Choir and Orchestra,'' both by <PERSON> Will </PERSON> <PERSON> Marion </PERSON> <PERSON> Cook </PERSON>. `` Swing Along'' got so much applause in 1912 it was performed again. The same thing happened on Friday. Another high point was two numbers by the Versatile Entertainers Quartet: piano, two banjos and snare drum. Conductor <PERSON> Maurice </PERSON> <PERSON> Peress </PERSON>, who organized the program, could n't find the quartet's music from the 1912 concert. He knew they were post-ragtime and pre-jazz but did n't know what they sounded like. But he turned up a 1916 recording and the quick-tempo `` Winter Nights'' and `` Down Home Rag'' on it were recreated Friday, starting with a delightfully trembling piano by <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Owens </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Male </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Choir </ORGANIZATION> and Boys Choir of <LOCATION> Harlem </LOCATION> sang <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s `` Clef Club March,'' `` Benedictus from the Mass in G'' by <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Bolin </PERSON> and <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Coleridge </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>'s `` By the Waters of Babylon.'' The diva engaged to sing `` <LOCATION> Swanee </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>'' in 1912 substituted `` My Heart at Thy Sweet Voice'' from the opera `` <PERSON> Samson </PERSON> and Delilah'' and <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Conrad </PERSON> did the same on Friday. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Warfield </PERSON> sang <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosamond </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>'s folk-sounding `` L'il Gal'' and he and Miss <PERSON> Conrad </PERSON> had fun dueting `` Play that Barber Shop Chord.'' <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Bates </PERSON> played a piano solo with flourishes, `` Dance Heroique.'' At a pre-concert lecture, Dr. <PERSON> Reid </PERSON> <PERSON> Badger </PERSON> talked about <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, who formed the <ORGANIZATION> Clef </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> as a booking agency for black musicians. He maintained a Clef Club Orchestra, with mandolins and banjos instead of second violins, for a strumming accompaniment, really the beginning of orchestral jazz. <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and his musicians often accompanied dancers <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON> and <PERSON> Irene </PERSON> <PERSON> Castle </PERSON>. The last piece on the program was a waltz he composed for them. <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> wrote for Broadway and in the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> in World War I, he organized a brass band. He is n't better known, <PERSON> Badger </PERSON> said, because he died at 38, stabbed by a deranged musician during a concert in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>.
