<SECOND>PM-Lost Fish,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fish Escapes After Marathon Battle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOLDOTNA, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Ploeger </PERSON> will have a well-documented fish story to tell when he gets back home to <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>. As with most fish stories, it will be about the one that got away. But this one is on the record. <PERSON> Ploeger </PERSON> attracted the attention of local news photographers and hundreds of onlookers as he battled a king salmon for nearly a day and a half before losing the fish and perhaps a world record. The length of the struggle coupled with the way the fish dragged boats up, down and across the river prompted speculation that it might have been the king of kings, the sport-caught salmon that finally would top the 100-pound mark. Kings that big have been caught commercially in <LOCATION> Cook </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Inlet </LOCATION> near the mouth of the Kenai, but the biggest ever taken on a rod and reel was 97 pounds, 4 ounces. The struggle began just after noon Wednesday when the 63-year-old <PERSON> Ploeger </PERSON>, a retired jailer from <LOCATION> Sandstone </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, hooked the fish about four miles upstream from the <LOCATION> Soldotna </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bridge </LOCATION> in south-central <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> about 75 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Anchorage </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Ploeger </PERSON> was fishing from a drift boat with a rookie guide, <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON>. <PERSON> Ploeger </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON> soon abandoned the drift boat, hopping aboard a passing powerboat after <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON> was unable to maneuver adequately through some boulder-studded rapids. He fought the fish that quickly was dubbed the `` Boss Hog'' through the night and all day Thursday. As word of the fish spread, the crowds grew. Local restaurants and businesses offered food and drink to <PERSON> Ploeger </PERSON> and the people helping him. Other guides shuttled fuel to the boat. <PERSON> Ploeger </PERSON> said there were hours of boredom punctuated by heart-stopping runs when the fish decided to go somewhere else. At one point, they thought they had him. `` He started coming up,'' said <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>, another guide recruited along the way. `` We thought he was worn out, but he must have gotten scared by the net.'' By Thursday evening, the shoreline was lined with people. Some brought lawn chairs, others fished themselves. At 8:36 p.m. they erupted in cheers when it seemed a world record had been set for the longest battle with a sport fish. According to the Guiness Book of World Records, a fisherman took 32 -LCB- hours to land a 1,600-pound marlin in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Ploeger </PERSON> had that beat _ if he could land the fish. But about four hours later, in the murky twilight that passes for night during <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> summers, the fish escaped _ leaving <PERSON> Ploeger </PERSON> and everyone else wondering how big it really was.
</TEXT>
