<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal court ruling could make oil companies pay more to clean up oil spills, including the massive spill from an Exxon tanker that polluted the coastline of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, says a congressman involved in the fight over liability for environmental accidents. A three-judge panel of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> for the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> unanimously ruled Friday the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> should rewrite its rules on paying for oil spills to include the costs of more than just the monetary value of animals killed. The decision raises chances `` that companies will have to pay the whole cost of restoring an environment,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Torricelli </PERSON>, D-N.J. <PERSON> Torricelli </PERSON> said the case could have a major impact on damage payments by oil companies involved in spills, such as the March 24 accident that occurred when the tanker <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valdez </ORGANIZATION> dumped 11 million gallons of crude oil into <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s pristine Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON>. `` This will make <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>'s exposure much greater,'' said <PERSON> Torricelli </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Levitt </PERSON> said the agency had n't studied the ruling and would n't have any comment He said no decision had been made on whether to appeal the case. The regulations were issued three years ago to implement the 1977 Clean Water Act and the 1980 Superfund law, which required the government to write regulations determining the monetary costs of oil spills. Several environmental groups and states sued over the regulations. Under the 1986 regulations, the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> created a computer model putting a dollar value for `` lost use'' of various types of wildlife. For example, the cost of a fur seal was set at $ 15, based on the expected value of a seal pelt. The cost of geese ranged up to $ 35, based on their popularity among hunters. But the appeals court said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, in writing the laws, had intended that repayment should be more broadly drawn to consider not simply the value of lost wildlife, but the larger cost of restoring the damaged environment. `` Because in some _ probably a majority _ of cases, lost-use value will be lower than the cost of restoration, <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION>'s rule will result in damages awards too small to pay for the costs or restoration,'' the ruling said. The <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has not yet decided on a damage assessment for either the Alaskan spill or three smaller spills which occurred last month off the coasts of <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>.
