<HEAD>`Star Wars' Particle Beam Fired Into Space</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Pentagon is studying results of a `` Star Wars'' test that is considered a key step in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> research to deploy futuristic weapons that could shoot powerful beams at enemy missiles. <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials on Friday confirmed completion of the test, which involved firing a beam of electrically neutral atomic particles into space for the first time. The BEAR test _ which stands for the Beam Experiment Aboard Rocket _ is designed to test how an accelerator of neutral particles would work in space. The experiment, which has been planned for more than a year, was completed early Thursday morning at the White Sands Missile Range in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, said Army Maj. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connell </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Strategic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Initiative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. Program scientists need to test whether neutral particle beams _ in this case, hydrogen atoms _ can be used to discriminate between real and mock Soviet warheads. The spokesman said it was `` presumptive'' to announce whether the test had been a success, since officials and scientists still need to study the results of the experiment over the weekend before releasing more information Monday. The experiment involved lifting into space _ just for a few minutes _ a neutral particle beam accelerator atop a small Aires rocket. Before the rocket returned to earth, the accelerator was to be turned on for collection of data on how it worked and how the beam moved. In June, a similar test was aborted when the rocket failed to ignite on command. The Star Wars program is a research effort aimed at developing lasers, beam accelerators and other futuristic weapons that could be used to automatically shoot down nuclear missiles fired at the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> or its allies. The Pentagon and <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> are spending $ 4 billion on such research this year.
