<HEAD>Inside Jneid Prison, Palestinians Run Their Own State</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Behind the cement walls, barbed-wire fences and guard towers of Jneid prison, 850 tough Palestinian prisoners are running their own state. The prison, built on the barren hills near the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> town of <LOCATION> Nablus </LOCATION>, is the largest for `` serious'' <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> guerrillas, those serving 20 years or more for attacks on Israeli targets. Among the inmates, dozens are serving life sentences, <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> said. The report Friday by the state television, the first time TV had been allowed to film inside the prison walls, showed something that looked more like a miniature state than a jail. The 850 inmates are kept in small, often crowded cells, each occupied by an average of 14 people. Jneid prison costs <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> more than $ 7.5 million a year. Unlike other prisons, there are reportedly no sexual assaults and no drugs in this one, practically run by a committee of six elected leaders. `` We have a committee of six prisoners who belong to different <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> factions. Each group has its own internal laws of selecting its representatives,'' said the prisoners' spokesman, <PERSON> Abdel </PERSON> <PERSON> Khader </PERSON> <PERSON> Fares </PERSON>. The committee was shown discussing prisoners' demands with warden <PERSON> Muffid </PERSON> <PERSON> Abbas </PERSON>, a Druse officer, and writing down a protocol of the talks. `` The prisoners are trying to expand all the time what they see as mini-autonomy. They demand improvements in all the fields: new teeth, union rights ... free passage from one prison section to another and a private doctor,'' the television said. <PERSON> Abbas </PERSON> said he usually responds positively to prisoners requests `` if it does not harm the security of the prison and if it is a human matter the prisoners need. They know it and they appreciate it.'' But Fares, serving a 15-year sentence for planting a bomb and a firearm attack on an Israeli bus, had a different opinion. He said inmates can pressure the authorities because of their influence on the <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> revolt that has raged for 19 months outside Jneid walls. `` They feel we are a honorable part of the Palestinian people in the -LRB- occupied -RRB- territories and we can influence the situation,'' he said. The prisoners refuse to work for the benefit of their Israeli enemies. But the discipline imposed by their leadership is tight and they clean their rooms, run the kitchen and have a tailor and a barber. The prison library has 4,000 books and the prisoners use it to conduct lessons in Hebrew, English, French, philosophy and Marxism, the television said. The prisoners also are allowed to spend 2 -LCB- hours in the prison courtyards. During one such break, prisoners were shown purposefully playing table tennis, basketball and chess or jogging around the courtyard. `` The terrorists view the prison as an academy for revolutionary education and for the creation of commanders,'' the television said. `` Every minute is reserved for useful conversations, studies, for strengthening the body and the spirit.'' <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> <PERSON> Shoshan </PERSON>, an officer of the prison administration, said the prisoners `` have their own doctrine. They have a specific way of life: sport activities, reading, education. They want to leave the prison more educated.'' Fares said the prisoners view their miniature Jneid state as a step bringing the Palestinians closer to their goal of independence. `` We are inside prisons, but everybody knows we are part of the Palestinian people, part of the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>,'' he said. During family visits, held in a large hall separated by wire mesh, the prisoners' conversations are not monitored and it showed the inmates passing written notes described as `` instructions and reports,'' the television said. `` This is the heart of the prison, a link to the territories,'' the television said. `` And if you ask the prisoners, the uprising started here, in security prisons.''
</TEXT>
