<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The capital of <LOCATION> Somalia </LOCATION> was reported calm today, one day after state radio said 10 people were killed and 32 injured when security forces opened fire on locals who attacked them with stones, knives and sticks. The clash broke out Friday near a mosque in a neighborhood of western <LOCATION> Mogadishu </LOCATION>, according to Somali state radio. The casualties included `` troublemakers'' and members of the security forces, according to a state radio broadcast monitored in <LOCATION> Nairobi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Somalia </LOCATION>'s western neighbor. A resident contacted by telephone Friday said it appeared troops had opened fire as Moslem worshipers left their place of prayer. Islam is the state religion in the impoverished East African nation of about 9 million. The resident, who spoke on condition he not be identified further, said gunfire erupted around midday in the capital on the shores of the <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> and continued sporadically through the afternoon. Residents contacted by telex from <LOCATION> Nairobi </LOCATION> said life in <LOCATION> Mogadishu </LOCATION> appeared to have returned to normal today and that a 6 p.m. to 6 a.m. curfew imposed Friday was lifted. A statement by the <ORGANIZATION> Somali </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, broadcast over state radio late Friday, said a group of `` troublemakers hiding behind the banner of religion'' caused the disturbances. Security forces tried to contain the situation peacefully, but opened fire after the `` troublemakers'' attacked them with stones, knives and sticks, according to the government statement. Ten people were killed and 32 wounded in the clash with casualties on both sides of the violence, said the statement. Friday is normally the Moslem Sabbath but July 14 also was the occasion for feast and celebration of the hajj, the Moslem faithfuls' pilgrimage to the holy city of <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION>. There were reports during the week that several Moslem religious leaders had been picked up by the authorities, but it was not known whether the alleged detentions had anything to do with Friday's violence Further information on the reported arrests was not available. Last Sunday, an unidentified gunman shot to death <PERSON> Mogadishu </PERSON>'s Roman Catholic Bishop <PERSON> Salvatore </PERSON> <PERSON> Pietro </PERSON> <PERSON> Colombo </PERSON> It also was not known whether the disturbances were connected to that incident. There are an estimated 2,000 Roman Catholics in <LOCATION> Somalia </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Somalia </LOCATION>, on the horn of <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> that juts into the <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION>, has been led since 1969 by the autocratic President <PERSON> Mohamed </PERSON> <PERSON> Siad </PERSON> <PERSON> Barre </PERSON> as a one-party state. Since 1981, <LOCATION> Somalia </LOCATION> has battled the <ORGANIZATION> Somali </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION>, a northern insurgency that demands <PERSON> Barre </PERSON>'s removal. Intensified fighting between the insurgents and the government over the last 18 months has driven more than 200,000 Somalis into refugee camps in neighboring <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>.
