<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Spreading strikes in the <LOCATION> Kuzbass </LOCATION> coal region of <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION> are causing heavy economic losses, newspapers reported today as officials appealed to miners in at least nine cities to return to work. Settlements were reported with miners in two cities, <LOCATION> Mezhdurechinsk </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Osiniki </LOCATION>, but strikes elsewhere have spread, the reports said. Soviet newspapers described a chaotic situation in the <LOCATION> Kuzbass </LOCATION>, an important coal-producing region about 1,600 miles east of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. It supplies fuel to the metallurgical industries in the <LOCATION> Ural </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION> to the west. Thousands of miners and their families were said to be meeting in town squares throughout the coal-producing basin to protest harsh living and working conditions. Authorities reported an end to the strike Thursday, but miners expanded their demands from economic issues, such as food, housing and health care, to broader demands for political change, Soviet reports said. The crisis was sharpest in the town of <LOCATION> Prokopevsk </LOCATION>, where production was virtually halted, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Sotsialisticheskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industriya </ORGANIZATION> reported in a dispatch from <LOCATION> Kemerov </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Oblast </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Kuzbass </LOCATION>. `` Events in the <LOCATION> Kuzbass </LOCATION> have taken a sharp turn,'' the newspaper reported. Although miners returned to work in <LOCATION> Mezhdurechensk </LOCATION>, in other mining towns in the basin `` the situation has sharply intensified.'' Mining Minister <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shchadov </PERSON> was in the area, rushing from mine to mine, `` spending many hours speaking to the strikers'' and trying to end the stoppage, the newspaper said. In addition to the agreement reached in <LOCATION> Mezhdurechensk </LOCATION>, where the strike began Tuesday, authorities also reached a settlement with miners in <LOCATION> Osiniki </LOCATION>, according to <PERSON> Sotsialisticheskaya </PERSON> <PERSON> Industriya </PERSON> and Pravda, another party newspaper. Strikes continued at <LOCATION> Prokopevsk </LOCATION>; at <LOCATION> Kisilevsk </LOCATION>, five out of 10 mines were on strike; two mines were on strike at Lenin-Kuznets; in <LOCATION> Kemerov </LOCATION>, the administrative center of the region, the Severnaya and Butovkskaya mines were on strike; miners were striking in <LOCATION> Novokuznetsk </LOCATION>, according to the newspaper reports. Miners in <LOCATION> Byelov </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Anzhero-Sudzhesk </PERSON> continued to work, but still made demands on authorities, the reports said. Reports said miners in nine cities were striking, although the published lists did not match. The reports said that despite a rather chaotic situation, rife with rumors, miners' strike committees that formed Friday were keeping social order. `` At their demand, sales of liquor were stopped and narcotics control points were established along highways,'' Pravda reported in a dispatch from its correspondent at the scene. It said that on Thursday in <LOCATION> Novokuznetsk </LOCATION> and on Friday in <LOCATION> Kemerov </LOCATION>, `` efforts were made by the so-called ` <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>' and several other informal organizations to spread anti-Soviet slogans, but they received a resolute rebuff.'' Authorities throughout the region tried to talk the miners back to work. `` Democracy means not only rights, but also responsbility, discipline and organization,'' <PERSON> Sotsialisticheskaya </PERSON> <PERSON> Industriya </PERSON> warned. Strikes were once hushed up and brutally suppressed in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, where they were considered a Western phenomenon resulting from capitalist exploitation. This year, however, coal strikes have generally ended after several days with government concessions. Last March, more than 100 coal miners in the <LOCATION> Ural </LOCATION> city of <LOCATION> Vorkuta </LOCATION> struck to protest increased work orders. In April, miners stayed underground in the Siberian city of <ORGANIZATION> Norilsk </ORGANIZATION> to demand a 30 percent wage increase. Twenty-four miners are reported to be staying underground in <LOCATION> Alexandria </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION> with demands similar to their <LOCATION> Kuzbass </LOCATION> counterparts.
