<FIRST>r a PM-SoybeanCorner     07-15 0618</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soybean Corner,0634</SECOND>
<HEAD>CFTC Will Investigate CBOT Actions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Commodities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> says it will review the trading positions of <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> directors to see if any of them profited from the drop in soybean prices precipitated by their emergency order earlier this week. The <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> made the announcement Friday as Italian agribusiness giant <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> said it would renew its court battle to recover losses from a <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> order forcing soybean traders to liquidate large positions in the market. <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Gardini </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finanzaria </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> SpA </ORGANIZATION>, reiterated in <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION> that his company's accumulation of futures contracts to take delivery of 23 million bushels of soybeans was legal. A Feruzzi spokesman said a lawsuit probably would be filed in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, but did not provide a timetable. The company also indicated it might seek compensation for unrealized profits as well as damage to its reputation. On Thursday, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Zaghel </PERSON> denied a request by two of the company's subsidiaries _ <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> SA </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> _ for a restraining order and a permanent injunction ending the directive issued Tuesday by the CBOT. <PERSON> Zagel </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> CBOT </ORGANIZATION> attorneys to file a motion to dismiss the lawsuit by Tuesday, with a response due July 24. <PERSON> Gardini </PERSON> did n't specify the amount of losses <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> suffered as a result of the board's order, which required all traders to reduce their July contract soybean holdings to 1 million bushels by the close of trading Thursday. <ORGANIZATION> CBOT </ORGANIZATION> directors have said they issued the liquidation order because the open July soybean contracts totaled about 40 million bushels and there were abnormally low levels of stocks available to satisfy the contracts _ a situation that would have resulted in a number of defaults without the exchange's intervention. Any player with a large enough share of the market _ a position referred to as `` cornering the market'' _ theoretically could force those on the other end of its futures contracts to deliver, possibly causing a scramble for supplies that would drive the price of its soybeans up sharply. Soybean prices for July delivery rose 6 cents to $ 7.03 -LCB- a bushel on Friday. Despite the gain, the price was still well below $ 7.26 a bushel, the level at which July soybeans settled on Tuesday before the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>'s directive. `` <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> and all major world traders are convinced that the board made a mistake and has to suffer the consequences,'' <PERSON> Gardini </PERSON> said about the potential lawsuit. <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> has said it accumulated large soybean supplies to keep its processing plants running and to meet export commitments, and also that its large futures market position was a hedge against price fluctuations. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> said it would review the trading positions of exchange directors and the minutes of the meeting at which the decision was made to force liquidation of soybean contracts. <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Karsten </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahlmann </PERSON> has said that none of those involved in the decision held a position in the soybean market when they voted to issue the emergency order. Meanwhile, Sen. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON>, D-Vt., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, expressed concern over the actions taken by the Board of Trade `` There have been serious allegations that there may have been an effort to manipulate the soybean futures market,'' he said `` I will insist on a full and rigorous investigation of any wrongdoing and that the perpetrators be punished to full extent of the law. `` If reforms are necessary to prevent these types of manipulations, I will insist on making them when this issue comes before my committee later this year.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> oversees the <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION>, which is up for reauthorization this year.
