<SECOND>PM-Green River,0664</SECOND>
<HEAD>Relative Hopes Green River Suspect is Killer; Police Sort Through
Belongings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARRIE FIGDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Seven years after his sister's body was found along the <LOCATION> Green </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, one of the first victims in the nation's worst serial murder case, <PERSON> Garrett </PERSON> <PERSON> Mills </PERSON> says he can only hope police have the killer Police began sorting through the 1,800 videotapes and 55 cartons and bags of materials seized from <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>, a former law student named in court papers as a `` viable suspect'' in the slayings. The sorting could take a month. <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> has not been charged in the case and he denies any involvement. His name became public late this week in an affidavit supporting a search warrant for two <LOCATION> Spokane </LOCATION> homes used by him. The affidavit said he was under investigation in the case and might be linked to at least 17 other homicide victims whose bodies were found along highways between <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Vancouver </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, and between <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Spokane </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Mills </PERSON>' sister, 16-year-old <PERSON> Opal </PERSON> <PERSON> Charmaine </PERSON> <PERSON> Mills </PERSON> was one of the 40 known <LOCATION> Green </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> victims. Police have blamed the killer for the disappearance of eight other young women. Ranging in age from 15 to 36, the female victims vanished between July 1982 and early 1984. Of the 40 corpses, 36 were found in the <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> area and four near <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>. Four remain unidentified The case takes its name from the site south of <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> where the first five corpses were found in the summer of 1982. `` I paid attention a lot at first, but I got tired of getting my hopes up,'' <PERSON> Mills </PERSON>, 25, said Friday of the investigation. He added, `` I hope it's him, but I do n't know.'' <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> is serving a one-year term in the county jail in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> for the burglary of a police equipment supply store in 1979 and additional time for walking away from a work-release center in 1981. He was rearrested in <LOCATION> Spokane </LOCATION> on Jan. 10. <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> was found after `` Manhunt,'' a nationally syndicated television show, aired a program in December about the <LOCATION> Green </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> killings. One tipster directed investigators to <ORGANIZATION> Gonzaga </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Spokane </LOCATION>, where <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> had attended classes for 3 -LCB- years and was president of the student bar. `` Whether or not this person is simply the victim of a bizarre set of circumstances or in fact responsible for some of the crimes in <LOCATION> King </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, we do n't know yet, and that's exactly what we're trying to determine by going through the material we recovered with the warrant,'' <ORGANIZATION> Green </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> River </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Task </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Commander <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> said Friday <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, who declined jailhouse interviews, `` is concerned he's being singled out as the answer to a longtime investigation,'' said his attorney, <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Beles </PERSON> `` He feels basically like anybody who is innocent of the offenses being looked at by the <ORGANIZATION> Green </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> River </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Task </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>. He is angry and frightened,'' said <PERSON> Beles </PERSON>. `` He's a colorful character, but he's no murderer.'' No personal items belonging to any <LOCATION> Green </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> victims were found in Wednesday's searches, <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> acknowledged the <ORGANIZATION> King </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> task force had found `` no smoking gun,'' but he said an initial study of 405 documents charting <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>' movements between 1981 and 1989 showed they sometimes closely paralleled the killings. Records seized when he was arrested show he traveled extensively between <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spokane </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Vancouver </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, under at least four aliases during the period, <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> said. After his arrest, <LOCATION> Spokane </LOCATION> authorities found in searches that <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> possessed several police-type vehicles, 26 license plates, 29 firearms and about 100 police badges, investigators said. The task force has long suspected the killer could be a police officer or someone posing as one, <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> said. In the affidavit, many who knew <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> said he liked pornography, frequented prostitutes and carried photographs of mutilated women.
