<HEAD>Five Trampled to Death in Fire Panic at Mecca Camp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JIDDAH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fire swept through a tent camp housing Moslems making the annual pilgrimage to <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION>, and five elderly Pakistanis were trampled to death in the ensuing panic, officials said today. Thirty-four others were hurt during the blaze that burned 220 tents Friday in the camp in <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION>, a civil defense official said in a statement distributed by the <ORGANIZATION> Saudi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. The camp was set up by the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Asian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilgrims </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, a Pakistani-based organization that arranges travel and accomodations for Moslems making the pilgrimage to the sacred Moslem city. The fire was caused by a flare from a gas cooker being used by one of the pilgrims, the statement said. The civil defense official said five elderly Pakistanis were trampled on as the pilgrims fled the camp. Fifteen of the injured remained hospitalized today and the others were treated and released. Such accidents are frequent during the pilgrimage season to <ORGANIZATION> Islam </ORGANIZATION>'s holiest shrines at <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Medina </PERSON>. About 2 million pilgrims from 80 countries gather for the rituals every year. The civil defense statement made it clear that authorities did not suspect sabotage at the camp. Two bombs exploded in <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION> on Monday at the height of the pilgrimage season. A Pakistani pilgrim was killed and 16 were wounded in the blasts.
