<HEAD>Dukakis Responds to Budget Woes, Drop in State's Bond Rating</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> took more heat for his 1990 budget cuts, which critics say could have been avoided had he acted swiftly to limit the state's financial troubles a year ago, during his presidential campaign. Demonstrators on Friday poured inside the <ORGANIZATION> Statehouse </ORGANIZATION> and marched to the doors of the governor's office chanting: `` No more cuts.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was not in, and they left peacefully about 20 minutes later. `` Let's send a message throughout the Commonwealth of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>,'' <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON> said at the demonstration. `` We are going to restore some semblance of decency and respect and compassion for people who need our help.'' Meanwhile, lawmakers vowed to restore $ 100 million in state aid to cities and towns that the governor vetoed to balance the fiscal 1990 budget. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> returned to the <ORGANIZATION> Statehouse </ORGANIZATION> later Friday to face other bad news: <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's dropped <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>' bond rating for the second time this year. The agency cited financial disarray in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> government. The move will add millions to borrowing costs. `` It's not unexpected. ... Had we demonstrated fiscal strength, we would n't have had to do what we did yesterday,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said of the budget cuts. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> defended his 1990 budget cuts as an `` essential part of getting the state back on track.'' The governor has come under fire for not acting swiftly when the state began to run into financial trouble a year ago. `` They've been whistling while <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> burned in this administration,'' said Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Flood </PERSON>, a Democrat who chairs the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Taxation </ORGANIZATION> committee. `` This is not a surprise to a lot of people,'' Flood said. `` It was avoidable and the administration chose to ignore the warnings.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> aides also announced the governor was postponing signing a bill legislators passed early Friday that would impose an income tax surcharge to make up the 1989 budget deficit and pay outstanding Medicaid debts. The measure is projected to raise $ 744 million over 18 months. `` He plans to sign it, assuming all the legal and technical questions are answered,'' said aide <PERSON> Mindy </PERSON> <PERSON> Lubber </PERSON>. Citizens for Limited Taxation and other anti-tax advocates say they'll take the income tax issue to the 1990 ballot to seek a refund.
