<HEAD>Shiite Clashes, Syrian-Christian Duels Amid Power Blackout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rival Shiite Moslem militias clashed in the slums of south <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> today and Syrian and <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> forces fought artillery battles across the capital amid a power blackout caused by fuel shortages. Police said one person was killed and four were wounded in the four-hour clash between the mainstream <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Amal </ORGANIZATION> militia, which is backed by <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>, and the pro-Iranian <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>, or Party of God. The two factions have clashed intermittently since April 1988 as they vied for dominance of 1.2 million Shiites, the largest single sect in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. By police count, the new casualties brought the overall toll of the power struggle to 561 killed and 1,554 wounded. Syrian troops deployed in west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> sent patrols at 4 a.m. into the low-income suburbs to disengage the militiamen and enforce a cease-fire between the secular Amal and the fundamentalist <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>, a police spokesman said. The spokesman, who can not be named in line with regulations, said Syrian gunners in west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> sporadically shelled the coast from east <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> to the port of <LOCATION> Byblos </LOCATION>, 28 miles to the north, maintaining their sea blockade of the Christian heartland. He said artillery fire fell around <LOCATION> Byblos </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Jounieh </LOCATION>, another port about 12 -LCB- miles north of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. No casualties were reported. Christian gunners of army commander Gen. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> fired back with 155mm guns, targeting positions along west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s seaside districts. The police spokesman said at least one round exploded `` within a few yards'' of a Syrian artillery emplacement in a deserted soccer field in the fashionable <LOCATION> Manara </LOCATION> district. `` We do n't know if the Syrians suffered any casualties. They usually evacuate their casualties to their own field hospitals and clinics which are not under our jurisdiction,'' the police spokesman said. <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>'s army command does not comment on losses among its 40,000 soldiers, stationed in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> under a 1976 Arab League peacekeeping mandate. The blockade of the Christian enclave has caused fuel oil shortages at <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s main power generating plant in suburban Zouk. The sea blockade has prevented shipments from arriving from abroad, and checkpoints around the enclave obstructed supplies from refineries in south and north <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. The electricity authority announced that as of today its generators will supply only the main water pumping station in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> and major hospitals and telecommunication switchboards with two hours of power every 24 hours on rotating basis. The public in both sectors of the divided capital and in the Christian heartland to the north will receive none. It was the second time that the city has plunged into total darkness since the confrontation between <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> and the Syrians began March 8. Last month's crisis was resolved after a partial lift of the land siege.
