<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> is pleased that <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> teen-ager <PERSON> Paula </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> was spared from the electric chair but regrets that four <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> military officers were executed, spokesman <PERSON> Joaquin </PERSON> <PERSON> Navarro </PERSON> said today. Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> had pleaded for clemency for Ms. <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>, who was sentenced to death for murdering an elderly Bible teacher when she was 15, and for former Gen. <PERSON> Arnaldo </PERSON> <PERSON> Ochoa </PERSON> and three other former Cuban officers convicted of drug trafficking. The <ORGANIZATION> Indiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Thursday commuted Ms. <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>'s sentence to 60 years in prison. Also Thursday, <PERSON> Ochoa </PERSON>, a war hero who fought with <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>'s revolution, and the three others were executed by a firing squad. `` One is very happy to know that <PERSON> Paula </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> received mercy,'' <PERSON> Navarro </PERSON> said in a statement released by the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> press office. `` On the other hand, one learned with regret the news of the execution in <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> of the four people for whom the Holy Father had asked for a gesture of clemency for understandable humanitarian reasons,'' he said.
