<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 3 grafs after 5th graf `Strong winds...' to UPDATE with
details on alert at Clark Air Base. Pickup 6th graf `Gordon is...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Typhoon <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON>, the strongest storm to threaten the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> this year, gained strength today as it roared toward <LOCATION> Luzon </LOCATION>, the country's main island, officials said. Storm warnings were raised over 10 provinces and at the six <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military bases. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military's <LOCATION> Far </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Network </LOCATION> described <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> as a `` super typhoon'' and said it would strike the northern island of <LOCATION> Luzon </LOCATION> early Sunday. At 5 p.m., <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> had peak winds of 128 mph and was heading toward <LOCATION> Luzon </LOCATION> at 14 mph from a position 270 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>. Earlier today, <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> had top winds of 116 mph. Strong winds buffeted <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> late today, but there were no reports of damage. At <LOCATION> Clark </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Air </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Base </LOCATION>, 50 miles north of <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>, officials canceled all inspections, training and other activities. The U.S.-run base's emergency rescue and clean-up units were placed on alert and non-essential personnel were ordered home The <ORGANIZATION> Far </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> East </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> said some <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlift </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> flights to and from <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> would also be canceled because of the typhoon. Heavy rains were expected in the <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> area late today, officials said. There are 40,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops, civilian employees and military dependents stationed at the six installations. <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> is expected to cut across the northern tip of <LOCATION> Luzon </LOCATION> before it moves out to the <LOCATIO