<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with nine dead, 49 injured, blast blamed
on guerrillas. ADDS byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A car bomb exploded near the center of the capital today, killing at least nine people and injuring 49, officials said. No one claimed responsibilty for the blast, but the government blamed Moslem guerrillas and unidentified `` foreign agents'' who support them. The guerrillas, based in neighboring <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and supported mainly by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, have been fighting for more than a decade to overthrow the Soviet-backed government. The bomb, hidden in a parked <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> truck, exploded at noon on <LOCATION> Nader </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Shah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Road </LOCATION> near the city's center, shattering windows 300 yards away and throwing bomb fragments 400 yards, police said. The blast left a crater six feet wide, six feet long and three feet deep, officials said. Hospital sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said at least 10 of the injured were in critical condition. `` I saw people on the road. There were people with their heads totally smashed,'' said <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Nabi </PERSON> <PERSON> Andar </PERSON>, who arrived at the scene five minutes after the blast. The explosion prompted stepped up security in the city of 2.25 million people. Police and soldiers were manning checkpoints around the city, and all vehicles were stopped and searched. `` The explosion is the work of our opponents and foreign agents who support them,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Nabi </PERSON> <PERSON> Amani </PERSON>. `` It was a very nasty thing to do just after Eid.'' Because of the Eid al-Adha, the three-day Moslem feast of sacrifice, the casualties were probably fewer. `` Had it been a normal day, at least 100 or 200 people may have died,'' said police officer <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Naim </PERSON>.
