<HEAD>Leftist Group Claims Responsibility for Attack on U.S. Servicemen</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to CORRECT that those injured were U.S. Army soldiers,
not members of North Dakota National Guard. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A leftist group has claimed responsibility for the bombing that injured seven <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> soldiers. `` Yankee soldiers are only safe in their own land because here they are the target of our bullets and explosives,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Morazanista </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> said in a communique issued Friday. The front, thought to be an arm of the outlawed <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> founded in 1979, has claimed responsibility for at least five other attacks, including three this year. Twenty-two <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> soldiers were injured in those incidents. `` The Morazanista sword is raised to expel or eliminate gringo invaders,'' said the communique, which was delivered to the newspaper <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prensa </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pedro </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sula </LOCATION>, 125 miles north of the capital. Police said a homemade bomb was thrown Thursday night at a group of nine <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> military policemen in civilian clothes as they passed by the <LOCATION> Lido </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Discotheque </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ceiba </LOCATION>, a coastal town 200 miles north of <LOCATION> Tegucigalpa </LOCATION>. The four most seriously injured were flown to a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military hospital in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said. Three others were being treated at <LOCATION> Enrique </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Soto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cano </LOCATION> air base near <LOCATION> Tegucigalpa </LOCATION>. Two escaped injury. All nine soldiers were from <ORGANIZATION> 459th </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION>, based at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Davis </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. They had come to <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> on temporary duty to take part in a series of U.S.-Honduran joint military exercises. The nine military policemen were on security-escort duty with a <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dakota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> convoy that was returning from drills in northern <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> to the base at <LOCATION> Soto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cano </LOCATION> when it stopped near <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ceiba </LOCATION> for the night. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Barclay </PERSON>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, said Thursday the nine military policemen went into town without leave. The front `` called on the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people to exert pressure on your <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, pressure so that your young sons will not die in foreign lands defending imperial causes. `` Our actions will continue claiming <ORGANIZATION> Yankee </ORGANIZATION> casualties in the pursuit of the war of liberation we are waging against the invader,'' the communique said. `` The national dignity can not be trampled with impunity.'' The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> maintains a permanent force of at least 1,200 troops in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> but thousands more rotate through every year on training missions.
