<HEAD>Budget Crunch Pitting Small Programs Against Popular Ones</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Outside the closed meeting rooms of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appropriations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> last week, the view was the same: clusters of men and women leaning against walls, talking, reading newspapers, killing time. It was a vigil of lobbyists, waiting for members of the Appropriations subcommittees to strike their deals and map in private how the government would spend more than half of the $ 1.17 trillion federal budget for the 1990 fiscal year. For many of the lobbyists, the wait was grim. After years of federal budget constraints, advocates for programs that could once count on generous government treatment are finding Uncle <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> stingier than he used to be. And they're competing with each other for the same scarce federal dollars. `` The first clue is that attendance here is 10 percent of what it usually is,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>, motioning down the <ORGANIZATION> Rayburn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Office Building corridor, as he and other lobbyists waited outside a meeting of the Appropriations labor, health and human services subcommittee. `` That's because there's no money.'' <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>, lobbying for low-income programs, was exaggerating, but only slightly. The labor subcommittee has jurisdiction over the government's health, welfare and education programs, a $ 155 billion slice of the federal pie for the coming fiscal year, which begins Oct. 1 But law requires that about two-thirds of that be spent on specific programs. The rest of it is up for grabs, and small programs with limited appeal to lawmakers are finding themselves competing for funds with politically popular initiatives for education, AIDS research, the homeless and the like. This strikes fear in the hearts of lobbyists for the government's less visible programs `` Poverty is n't popular,'' said <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>. `` What we're seeing is an understated but very definite realignment of government priorities. We're seeing interest flow in three or four areas, and an ending of the government role in other areas.'' Outside another closed door, this one in the Capitol basement, another group of lobbyists waited as the Appropriations treasury and <ORGANIZATION> postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> subcommittee </ORGANIZATION> wrote its $ 18.5 billion bill. Some of them were working on behalf of postal subsidies for small newspapers, charities, unions and schools, which are entitled to lower mailing rates. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration had tried to terminate the $ 430 million program, and President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has proposed limiting it. Advocates were hoping to win a slight increase for the subsidies, but they acknowledged they faced formidable competition for federal funds from another area within the subcommittee's jurisdiction. `` The big issue in this committee is drug enforcement,'' said <PERSON> Carolyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Emigh </PERSON>, counsel for the <ORGANIZATION> Non-Profit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mailers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. Anti-drug programs are among the most popular programs on Capitol Hill these days, as lawmakers heed polls indicating that drugs are the foremost problem on the minds of voters. Their appeal makes it easy for members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to lavish them with money. `` Right now drugs are pretty high on the list,'' Sen. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, D-W. <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appropriations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, acknowledged in an Congressional spending priorities are easy to discern by studying the way the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appropriations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> divided up the $ 658 billion it oversees among its 13 subcommittees. The three largest increases over 1989 spending levels were of $ 5.3 billion to the subcommittee that oversees veterans, housing, science and space programs; $ 4 billion to the panel that controls health and education; and $ 1.8 billion to the subcommittee with jurisdiction over law enforcement. That still left <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> fielding complaints at a committee meeting last week that several subcommittees had been granted too little money. The tight money seems not to have stopped lawmakers themselves from seeking funds for projects within their home districts, however. <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> said the Appropriations interior subcommittee, which he also chairs, has so far received 1,971 requests for money for projects. And Sen. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Harkin </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Iowa </LOCATION>, chairman of the Appropriations labor, health and human services panel, said he had gotten 455 requests.
