<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Debt,0797</SECOND>
<HEAD>Debt Reduction Vital To Economic Recovery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> badly needs the help President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is offering to reduce payments on its foreign debt, but even with substantial relief, coaxing the country out of seven years of stagnation may be a slow process. `` Mexican as well as foreign investors are waiting for the starting flag that the solution to the debt negotiations will give,'' said President <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON>, who met with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> last week. Attention was focused last week on talks between <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and creditor banks as world leaders gathered in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> for an economic summit. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> wanted an agreement as a showpiece for its strategy to reduce the Third World's $ 1.3 trillion debt. The lengthy negotiations apparently snagged, and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> tried to give them a boost by offering <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> a temporary loan of $ 1 billion to $ 2 billion. The offer appeared to be aimed at showing banks and other creditor nations the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would put its money where its mouth is. For <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, an agreement would mean both money and a psychological boost, two elements needed to reignite growth. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> owes $ 107.4 billion and maintains that its economy is hobbled because it must spend $ 16 billion every year to pay the interest and principal. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> wants to reduce those payments by $ 7 billion, money that could then be invested in industrial expansion to provide jobs. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> has one million young people entering the job market every year, creating tremendous social pressure _ some of which is relieved by emigration to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. What can happen when a social system is under stress was seen earlier this year when rioting broke out in <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>, and food stores were looted in <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>. One private economist compared <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> to a family whose loan payments leave little left over even for basics like rent, food or transportation. The family cuts spending and tries to increase its income to avoid taking on more loans, but all its money goes into the loan payments and it remains poor. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> incurred most of its debt between 1976 and 1982, when eager banks pressed money on a nation that thought oil had made it rich. But the price of oil crashed and growth in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> for the past six years has averaged about zero. The buying power of the average paycheck has been cut in half. `` When we talk about growth, it means to stop the fall in buying power, to stop the process of impoverishment of Mexican society,'' said <PERSON> Jacobo </PERSON> <PERSON> Zaidenweber </PERSON>, a textile manufacturer who is president of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S.-Mexico </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>. To turn the situation around requires investment. That's where foreign debt reduction comes in. `` If a satisfactory agreement with respect to the debt is reached, the necessary conditions to resume growth will be there,'' said <PERSON> Nora </PERSON> <PERSON> Lustig </PERSON>, an economics professor at the <ORGANIZATION> Colegio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mexico </ORGANIZATION> and a visiting fellow at the <ORGANIZATION> Brookings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The agreement being discussed by the banks and <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> calls for approximately 35 percent of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s debt to be written off and for other adjustments in the debt structure to reduce the load. Some banks are reportedly asking for a clause that would increase payments once <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s economy improves, but upping payments might also cut off a recovery. Part of what <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> gains will go to buying back debt at a discount, economists say. The rest can be used for investment in infrastructure that could prime the pump for the private sector. With fewer payments to make, the government will need to borrow less money. That will put less pressure on domestic credit markets and make more money available for the private sector at lower rates. Increased confidence would attract foreign investment and, perhaps even more important, help bring back billions invested abroad by wealthy Mexicans. Capital flight, according to recent reports, has already ceased. <PERSON> Zaidenweber </PERSON> said a debt agreement will help him expand his textile plants to compete with imports and increase exports. `` We have to grow to lower costs and get more modern equipment to increase quality,'' he said. The government has set the stage for recovery with a program that has pushed free-market reforms. <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> has been a driving force there, first as budget director, now as president. Nevertheless, <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mexico </ORGANIZATION> director <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> Mancera </PERSON> was cautious. `` The resources of the country are scarce. It's evident there is n't enough for everything we would like to do,'' the daily <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financiero </ORGANIZATION> quoted him as saying. `` Recovery will most likely be slow in the beginning,'' Ms. <PERSON> Lustig </PERSON> said, `` but we might get a surprise.''
</TEXT>
