<DATELINE>SIOUX FALLS, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The remains of ancient <ORGANIZATION> Seminole </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indians </ORGANIZATION> dug up in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> will be reburied at Wounded Knee next month in a ceremony to be conducted by members of the <ORGANIZATION> Oglala </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sioux </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribe </ORGANIZATION>. The ceremony is scheduled for Aug. 11, at the Wounded Knee Cemetery where about 200 Indians killed by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops in 1890 are buried. The reburial of the prehistoric remains will follow a symposium on archaeological ethics and the treatment of the dead to be held at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dakota </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Vermillion </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Zimmerman </PERSON>, a USD professor. Included in the 1,200 pounds of remains are pieces of pottery and the dirt that was unearthed along with the bone fragments. `` The <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> earth will be with them,'' <PERSON> Zimmerman </PERSON> said. The remains, originally dug up by researchers and later given to the Seminoles, were sent to the university by tribal members four years ago under the condition that they not be used for scienctific study, he said. Recently, <LOCATION> Seminole </LOCATION> tribe members asked USD officials to give the remains to members of the <LOCATION> Oglala </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tribe </LOCATION> for burial. The Oglalas make up the majority of the population on the <LOCATION> Pine </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ridge </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Reservation </LOCATION> where Wounded Knee is located. But remains from other distant Indian tribes have in recent years been sent to Wounded Knee for burial. The issue of reburial has become a heated topic in archaeological circles over the last decade. It's a subject that is often boiled down to a case of science vs. religion, <PERSON> Zimmerman </PERSON> said. `` The whole issue of reburial is an issue that started primarily in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> and among native American Indians,'' he said. `` What's happened over the last decade and a half is -LRB- indigenous peoples -RRB- have become more politically active on this issue and see it as a two-pronged concern `` Is it a violation of religious freedom ... and who gets to use these remains and where do they put them?'' `` It is n't science vs. religion, it is who controls the past,'' he said. Archaelogists from about 20 countries and representatives from North American Indian tribes and other indigenous people from around the world are expected to attend the meeting.
