<HEAD>Mandela at Center of Political Furor in South Africa</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 45-minute chat between <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> and President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> has thrown government and anti-apartheid forces off balance as they try to adjust their policies to the unprecedented event. The meeting July 5 between the imprisoned <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> leader and the retiring president caused confusion on all sides. The exiled <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> described the meeting as a publicity stunt, but as praise poured in from other anti-apartheid groups, it withheld further comment. It may be that the 73-year-old <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, facing forced retirement at the hands of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> he controlled for 10 years, gave history a push just to spite his designated successor. The heir apparent, F.W. <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Klerk </PERSON>, has not commented on the meeting in <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION>, and the government seems to be scrambling to explain it without losing too many votes to the white right-wing in September parliamentary elections. Apparently preparing the groundwork for <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>'s release, the government is transforming its portrayal of him _ from a violent revolutionary to a statesman worthy of negotiating with the nation's white leaders Ambiguity extends even to <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>, who turns 71 on July 18 and is serving a life term for sabotage and plotting to overthrow the government. He insists he has not changed his views during 27 years in prison. He has not met the government's demand for an outright renunciation of violence, and he continues to call for the removal of a ban on the exiled <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION>. But <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>, in a statement released by <ORGANIZATION> Prison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> a week after he met <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, said, `` I only would like to contribute to the creation of the climate which would promote peace in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>.'' The policy of the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> and most sympathetic anti-apartheid groups has been that no negotiations with the government are possible until <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> is freed. Yet the meeting and <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>'s statement can be interpreted as indicating <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> has already begun a form of negotiation. Justice Minister <PERSON> Kobie </PERSON> <PERSON> Coetsee </PERSON>, who arranged and attended the meeting at <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s official residence, first described it as `` a courtesy visit.'' A week later he declared it `` a breakthrough.'' Foreign Minister <PERSON> Pik </PERSON> <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, mindful of the need to improve <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s image abroad, called it `` an event of the utmost historic importance.'' Information Minister <PERSON> Stoffel </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> der </PERSON> <PERSON> Merwe </PERSON>, aware of the danger of startling white voters before the elections, said the meeting was `` part of the broader process of preparing the groundwork for future negotiations.'' Only the extreme-right, pro-apartheid <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> has made its position clear. <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Andries </PERSON> <PERSON> Treurnicht </PERSON> attacked the government for talking to the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> and said its `` attempt to enhance <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>'s status to that of a folk hero is transparent and will not work.'' Pro-government news media presented <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>'s commitment to peace as a dramatic change. But it is new in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> only because <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>'s views have been suppressed for so long. <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>'s words made headlines around the country and were read on government-run television and radio. His picture, which can not be published legally, has been printed in major newspapers, whose editors believe they will not be prosecuted. First reactions from <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>'s wife, <PERSON> Winnie </PERSON>, and from the Rev. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Chikane </PERSON>, secretary-general of the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Churches </ORGANIZATION>, suggested <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> may have been forced into the meeting or been unaware of its implications. Mrs. <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> and <PERSON> Chikane </PERSON> reversed course after <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>'s statement, saying the discussions were a positive development rather than a government ploy <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Sebina </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Lusaka </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Zambia </LOCATION>, `` It would be wrong for anybody to believe that the meeting signified the start of negotiations between the black people of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> government.'' He did not react to <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>'s statement, but his comment contained an important shift. He referred to the `` government,'' instead of the `` apartheid regime.'' <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> as a free man, able to act as a politician rather than a symbol, poses problems that the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> has not fully addressed. Although he is regarded as the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> leader, the highest post <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> held before the organization was outlawed in 1960 was deputy-president general. The <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> has a president, <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> Tambo </PERSON>, who has lived in exile for 29 years. <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> had set guidelines for the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION>'s military wing calling for carefully considered attacks on government targets, and arguing against acts that would cause indiscriminate deaths, as the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION>'s bombing campaign has done The majority of <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>'s supporters were born after he was jailed, have never heard his words, and have grown up in an environment of black-on-black township political strife that did not exist in 1962. `` There has been built up around him such a folklore hero role that he would be recieved as a hero,'' said <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> <PERSON> Suzman </PERSON>, a white, anti-apartheid member of Parliament. `` But how does one know what he's going to suggest to them and what they are prepared to accept?''
</TEXT>
