<DATELINE>AMSTELVEEN, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A dentist was accused of passing state secrets to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> after police found military hardware and classified documents in his apartment, newspapers reported Saturday. The 47-year-old man allegedly spied for the Soviet military intelligence service, <ORGANIZATION> GRU </ORGANIZATION>, over an eight-year period, according to the reports. The man, who runs an import-export business in addition to his dental practice in this <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION> suburb, was arrested May 17 when he was about to fly out of the country, the press reports said. They said the man was released last week pending charges. Neither the man nor his firm was identified in any of the reports, in line with <LOCATION> Dutch </LOCATION> media practice on police and judicial cases. The <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION> newspaper <ORGANIZATION> De </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Volkskrant </ORGANIZATION> said police and investigators of the <ORGANIZATION> Dutch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Domestic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> found large numbers of classified documents on military products made by Dutch firms inside the man's apartment. However, it was not clear from any of the reports what material the man allegedly passed to the Soviets, or how much damage the activities had caused. The <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, which is responsible for counterespionage, was closed and not immediately available for comment. According to <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Volkskrant </PERSON>, the papers found in the apartment related to various kinds of high-technology military products, including computer systems. If convicted of espionage, the man could face a 15-year prison term. Dutch officials have repeatedly said the <ORGANIZATION> GRU </ORGANIZATION> and its civilian counterpart, the <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION>, have bee