<DATELINE>JOHNSON CITY, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Singer-songwriter <PERSON> Loudon </PERSON> <PERSON> Wainwright </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> does n't care if he's making people laugh or cry as long as they're feeling something. `` I'd like to try to do both, preferably at the same time,'' he said. `` The most painful things quite often can be funny.'' <PERSON> Wainwright </PERSON>, 42, has made a career out of being the comedian and melancholy guy. His first hit, in 1972, was about a dead skunk, but his latest album is titled `` Therapy.'' `` I want to be known as a guy who writes good songs,'' he said Tuesday from <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. `` And if it's humorous, great. If it's serious or tragicomedy or whatever you want to call it, you know, as long as it's good and it affects people.'' <PERSON> Wainwright </PERSON> has yet to score a Grammy, though he's been nominated twice. The former drama student also has acted on stage, screen and television. `` We have n't got there yet,'' said <PERSON> Wainwright </PERSON>, who maintains homes in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. `` It'll be the year that I win the Grammy, the Oscar and the <PERSON> Tony </PERSON>.''
