<FIRST>u i AM-China-Summer Bjt   07-15 0754</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Summer, Bjt,0780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fear Underlies Sleepy Summer in Beijing</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Martial law has not changed the summer rhythm of this dusty city. A hot sun hypnotizes its 10 million residents into slow motion, and soldiers stand sleepily under bright umbrellas. The soldiers squint and play idly with the safety catches on their automatic rifles. It is possible to catch them napping, stocking feet sticking out the windows of a parked army jeep. Some people stroll up to them boldly, ask them where they are from and offer them soda. But despite the mantra-like assurances of city authorities, <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> has not returned to normal. Arrests continue of people who took part in the student-led protests for democratic reform. Some people are taken away as looking `` suspicious,'' questioned, beaten and released. A bookstore where liberals used to meet has been closed. The latest issue of a magazine has been halted at the post office because of an article that censors deemed harmful. Books by scholars who are wanted by police have been banned, and <ORGANIZATION> Culture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> workers have raided private bookstalls to seize copies. At least one book has been banned even as it was being published, a Chinese source said. Countless people pass their days in fear of punishment under the government's harsh new policy emphasizing class struggle and the need to stamp out Western-style liberalism. `` I invited you to come to our home for lunch and we bought beer and things to make dumplings, but I'm sorry, you ca n't come,'' a <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> intellectual said with embarrassment as he met a Western friend recently. `` They said foreigners should not come to our homes,'' he explained. Even meeting a Westerner in public made him fearful, and he cast nervous glances around him. `` Things will get better, let's wait a few months,'' he said before merging with relief into the crowd. He was brave to keep the appointment. Many Chinese have stopped answering their telephones and few are willing to talk to foreigners. `` It's like the Cultural Revolution,'' said a <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> reporter who was in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> during the 1966-76 upheaval, during which almost all contact between Chinese and foreigners was forbidden. Asked about the restrictions, government spokesman <PERSON> Yuan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mu </PERSON> said it was for the foreigners' protection `` because there are so many Chinese and you do n't know who is good and who is bad. It is not written on their foreheads.'' All over the city, hundreds of thousands of teachers, doctors, journalists and factory workers who cheered or joined in the 7-week-long protests face investigation. Most will not be arrested, predicted a Chinese source, but they will spend several tense weeks as <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> officials at their work units investigate their cases. At a minimum, they will be required to acknowledge the error of their ways, the source said. Political education already has begun for work units, protesters and bystanders alike. Graduating college students spent several weeks studying speeches by top leaders condemning the protests as the work of traitors. Participants were urged to speak their hearts, according to one official newspaper, but several said they just repeated words from the speeches. Teachers also have had long study sessions. Education appears lightest for production line workers, who are being pressed to make up for the losses of the weeks of protest. Testimonials from protesters have begun appearing in the official media, confessing their actions but saying they now understand and approve the government's crackdown. `` Motherland, country, we were wrong,'' said one statement attributed to a group of students. The relaxed attitude of the soldiers belies the tight security. New plainclothes guards watch comings and goings at foreign apartment compounds and several embassies, including the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>, where leading dissident <PERSON> Fang </PERSON> <PERSON> Lizhi </PERSON> has taken shelter. Chinese who enter a major office tower must show identification. Switchboard operators at some Chinese government units demand callers identify themselves before putting them through. Soldiers check the papers of Chinese who emerge from their stifling homes at night to catch a cool breeze on the sidewalk. After 11 p.m., soldiers stop cars at main intersections and question drivers. When an army motorcycle broke down during the day on one street, a jeep of armed soldiers stopped to guard it while repairs were made. When two bicyclists got into an argument, drawing a small crowd, soldiers quickly dispersed it. And yet the security appears to have gaps. A foreigner recently reported seeing a naked body floating in a canal near his home.
</TEXT>
