<HEAD>Bentsen Wants Rural Areas Included In Drug-Control Blueprint</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The national anti-drug strategy due out this fall must look beyond the big cities and address the rapid spread of the cocaine derivative crack to rural areas, Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said Saturday. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said he is asking national drug control director <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, who is drawiing up the anti-drug blueprint, to include `` measures to combat the serious and growing problem of drug abuse in smaller towns and the rural countryside.'' The <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Democrat said he wants to be sure the <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> `` does n't limit its efforts to just the big dealers and the big cities, that we include rural and small towns too.'' In one rural <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> area, authorities report an 80 percent increase in crack cases in just one year, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said. `` If you ignore that kind of an increase you do so at your own peril,'' <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said in his letter to <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>. `` It's absolutely imperative that we have an overall program that takes care of not just the large cities but the small towns, rural areas in addition.'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> must complete the first comprehensive national drug-control plan by Sept. 5. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said he was concerned about a recent <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> memorandum that said crack dealers in smaller communities `` do not merit full federal investigative efforts'' since they typically limit their sales to small quantities. A <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> survey in 1986 found crack available in 28 states and the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>. Another DEA survey in December 1987 found that number had jumped to 45 states, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said. And while the survey noted that crack cocaine remained primarily an inner city problem, it noted that `` recent seizures indicate that crack has appeared in rural parts of <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>.''
