<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Eight weeks before the primary <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON>'s job is clear: He either makes up ground fast or makes plans to step aside for <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s first black mayor, or its first Republican mayor in two decades. `` Sixteen points in this day and age is not an insurmountable margin by any means, as I was telling President <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>,'' quipped <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Garth </PERSON>, <PERSON> Koch </PERSON>'s media adviser, on Friday. <PERSON> Garth </PERSON> was as surprised as anyone Thursday when <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> chose a midday radio talk show to announce officially his candidacy for an unprecedented fourth term. Not that there was any doubt _ he made his intentions obvious last year and started television ads this month. `` I think I've done a lot of good things. I've done a couple of stupid things,'' said <PERSON> Koch </PERSON>, 64. `` I've done things that I would do over and differently but that's water over the dam. `` I believe that my three terms will be perceived historically as very good for the city of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>.'' His opponents, and many pundits, think the outspoken <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> already is history. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Dinkins </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> borough president, leads <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> by 13 to 15 points in Democratic polls; the latest had him ahead 45 percent to 31 percent. Getting more than 40 percent of the vote in the Sept. 12 primary would enable <PERSON> Dinkins </PERSON> to avoid a primary runoff. The likely Republican is former federal prosecutor <PERSON> Rudolph </PERSON> <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON>, who is far ahead of his <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> rival, cosmetics heir <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Lauder </PERSON>. A <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News-WABC-TV </ORGANIZATION>