<HEAD>Mineworkers Union Seeks Huge Anti-Apartheid Coalition</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-SAfrica-Mandela, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The country's largest black union said Saturday it wants to form a huge anti-apartheid coalition to coordinate strategies among opposition groups. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mineworkers </ORGANIZATION> said it will seek to arrange a conference no later than October to bring together the `` core forces of the mass democratic movement.'' `` It is important to win over all anti-apartheid forces to our side,'' said the union, which has about 300,000 members. Anti-apartheid groups have been urgently trying to formulate unified strategies since the July 5 meeting between President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> and jailed black nationalist <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>, leader of the <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. Opposition groups initially dismissed the talks as government propaganda that involved no shift in policy. But several organizations revised their assessment and called it a positive development after <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> released a statement Wednesday indicating he welcomed the chance to talk with <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>. The mineworkers union said the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> African Trade Unions _ the country's largest labor federation _ and the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> _ the largest anti-apartheid coalition _ would play leading roles in the coalition it sought to establish. However, both groups are banned from participating in political activities. The mineworkers did not explain how these organizations could become active in politics. The outlawed <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> and other anti-apartheid groups have said there can be no negotiations with the government until it meets several basic demands, such as freeing all political prisoners, legalizing banned organizations and lifting the state of emergency. The anti-apartheid movement has found it increasingly difficult to organize under the 3-year-old state of emergency, during which more than 30 opposition groups have been banned. <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> has been imprisoned since 1962 and is serving a life sentence for sabotage and plotting to overthrow the government. His meeting with <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> suggests the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> leader is willing to talk with the government, though his demand for a non-racial democracy in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> is unchanged. The white-led government also appears to have eased its policy of having no contact with the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION>, which it labels a terrorist organization. Under <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s apartheid policies, the 28 million blacks have no voice in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the government and economy, while maintaining separate neighborhoods, schools and health facilities.
