<HEAD>Four More Years for Coleman Young?</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-NYC Mayoral, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRETEL WIKLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Mayor <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON> is preparing to announce whether he will run for a fifth term this week as even some of his supporters say he should step down at age 71. Eight weeks remain before the Sept. 12 non-partisan primary when voters will select two candidates for a Nov. 7 runoff. Young, the city's first black mayor, is expected to announce his plans Tuesday. He has hinted for months that he would run but left open the possibility he would retire. `` If I announce, then I will announce when I announce,'' <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said, a comment typical in tone of his chilly relations with reporters, which his aides blame in part on media racism. Young, if he does run for another four-year term, would enter as the solid front-runner, able to cite progress in areas such as integrating the police force but also in spite of an array of problems facing the city. He has a largely untapped campaign fund estimated at $ 5 million, and is considered to hold a commanding lead over accountant <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Barrow </PERSON>, who won the right to face him in the runoff four years ago and is expected to do so again this year. <PERSON> Barrow </PERSON> reportedly has less than $ 300,000 available for his campaign. Young, a former union organizer, has been in office since 1973, the same year <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Maynard </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> came to power in the early generation of big-city black mayors. <PERSON> Barrow </PERSON>, 40, is founder and president of <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>'s largest minority-owned accounting firm and a nephew of the late boxing great <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Louis </PERSON>. He received only 39 percent of the vote when he ran against <PERSON> Young </PERSON> in 1985, but this year has been campaigning door-to-door, while <PERSON> Youn