ON> <PERSON> Conyers </PERSON> also denies he has any interest in being mayor. Young, an ardent civil rights activist in this predominantly black city, seemed to emerge unscathed politically last year after criticizing the Rev. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s presidential campaign, saying a black man had no legitimate chance of winning and backing <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. But the mayor has other problems. <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>'s population has dropped from about 2 million in 1950 to about 1 million today. The flight to outlying suburbs has left behind thousands of boarded-up, burned-out houses that attract drug dealers and other crime. Some fed-up residents, tired of waiting for city demolition crews, have even torn down abandoned houses themselves. Though Young's opponents have avoided mention of it, <PERSON> Young </PERSON> also faces a paternity suit filed against him by <PERSON> Annivory </PERSON> <PERSON> Calvert </PERSON>, a former assistant director in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Works </ORGANIZATION> who now lives in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. Young, who is single, at first denied the child was his. But in May, blood tests proved he was the father of Ms. <PERSON> Calvert </PERSON>'s 6-year-old son, <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Loving </PERSON> The mayor is paying $ 200 a week in child support until the court sets a final amount. Other issues facing the mayor include: _ <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>'s trash-burning incinerator, which has angered environmentalists who say pollution standards for the $ 420 million project to create energy by burning wastes are too low _ A deal involving the city's acquisition of land for a $ 1 billion <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> assembly plant, which is being investigated by a federal grand jury amid charges the city paid $ 40 million for used machinery worth $ 2 million in condemned buildings on the plant site There's no suggestion that <PERSON> Young </PERSON> himself is suspected of criminal wrongdoing. _ Young's hostile relations with reporters, and negative coverage that the mayor's staff blames on institutional racism Young rebuffed numerous requests for an interview by The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. Young has been particularly unhappy with local coverage of the police force, a once-predominantly white department whose racial integration has been a source of pride for the mayor. <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, <PERSON> Young </PERSON>'s chief executive assistant, said the makeover of the force was ignored by local media. Specifically, <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said, a group of newspaper columnists `` constantly dump on the mayor.'' `` We do think there is a little different standard for <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>,'' he said. `` I'm not saying that it is conscious or deliberate.''
