<HEAD>Justice Investigates Questionable Grants By Former Agency Official</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> has turned over to the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> records that show a former top official passed over financially-strapped housing projects in favor of doling out emergency funds to a one-time business associate and donors to his pet charity. The <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>'s inspector general concluded in a March audit that at least 11 of 25 projects funded through the emergency set-aide program in 1987 and 1988 did not meet agency guidelines. Several well-connected developers received multiple awards from the fund. Seven projects that exceeded guidelines were bypassed; they eventually went under and had to be taken over by <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>, which over time will cost the government millions of dollars, the auditors concluded. <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> investigators said those decisions were made by <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Demery </PERSON>, who at the time was <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>'s assistant secretary for housing. He left the agency last year and opened a consulting business but has been beleaguered of late with questions about his actions at <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>. The department is the focus of internal, congressional and <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> investigations of fraud, mismanagement and influence-peddling during President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s tenure. <PERSON> Demery </PERSON>, 39, in a brief interview Thursday, denied favoritism played a role in any funding decisions. `` It was all done on the merits,'' he said. But department officials, in the report that <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> sources said has been forwarded to Justice as part of its investigation of the troubled housing agency, said `` assistance was provided to projects that were neither approvable under the regulations nor demonstrated an emergency need.'' The sources spoke on condition they not be identified. The Section 8 loan management set aside fund is used to help struggling housing projects that already have some type of government financing. Guidelines allow the emergency assistance in cases when low occupancy or other problems have caused severe financial problems. The infusion of <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> money, through the use of low-income rent subsidies, is designed to prevent a more costly default. The emergency accounts totaled $ 42 million during the two-year audit period; $ 36 million of that went to the 11 questionable projects chosen by <PERSON> Demery </PERSON> for help. Of those 11, six did not demonstrate a cash-flow problem and the five others were ineligible for funding because of poor maintenance, management or other problems, <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> investigators concluded. In addition, some of the projects had not even applied locally for funding, and in other cases local <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> officials had rejected applications, the auditors said. The investigators said they could find no documentation to support <PERSON> Demery </PERSON>'s decisions. What can be found through review of the <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> records, <PERSON> Demery </PERSON>'s financial disclosure statements and other records is that <PERSON> Demery </PERSON> had past ties to at least one of the developers who got emergency funding Several others were contributors to FOOD for <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, a Michigan-based charity <PERSON> Demery </PERSON> helped found. A separate audit of a <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> rehabilitation program also found scores of occasions in which FOOD donors won lucrative government subsidies. <PERSON> Demery </PERSON> attended several f