project auditors said did not meet requirements for emergency aid. The project is owned by a group called <ORGANIZATION> PM </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> One </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which donated $ 2,000 to FOOD. A related company also donated to the charity. The president of <ORGANIZATION> PM </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> One </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Armstead </PERSON>, did not return a telephone call to his <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> office. <PERSON> Demery </PERSON> in 1984 received a fee of at least $ 5,000 from a related company, <ORGANIZATION> PMI </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, for consulting work. At the time he was a <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> real estate consultant and mortgage broker who did some <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> contracting work. _ One of the owners of another projects that received emergency assistance, <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON>, also donated $ 1,000 to FOOD in October 1987. The auditors, however, did not question the eligibility of that project, <ORGANIZATION> Somerset </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> apartments in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Royalton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, which received $ 180,000 from <PERSON> Demery </PERSON>. _ Seven of the 25 projects given emergency funding over the two-year period were in <PERSON> Demery </PERSON>'s home state of <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>. His phone logs show he kept close ties with his business associates there, often receiving several calls a day from <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> developers. <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> <PERSON> Seligman </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Southfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, developer who got emergency assistance for three projects that auditors said were not eligible, said the frequency of the awards to <LOCATION> Michigan <