ty, respect and ability.'' Twenty of 29 ambassadorial nomination made by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in the first six months of his administration have gone to non-professionals, many of them large contributors to <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> causes, committee sources said. <PERSON> Sarbanes </PERSON> says the appointments are larding the diplomatic corps with amateurs rewarded for purely political services. `` Political throwaways,'' <PERSON> Sarbanes </PERSON> calls them. `` I think the time has come, very frankly, to get off the money merry-go-round and ask some very difficult questions, essentially about when extensive political contributions are going to be a sufficient basis to gain an ambassadorial nomination,'' <PERSON> Sarbanes </PERSON> told the committee last month. `` It's not true in every instance, but in most of these cases you seem to have to be over the $ 100,000 mark in order to make the consideration list,'' <PERSON> Sarbanes </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Sarbanes </PERSON> says he is not against political ambassadors as such, noting that many of them compiled distinguished records. `` It is not the political ambassadors that are the problem,'' <PERSON> Sarbanes </PERSON> said. `` It is ambassadors without qualifications.''
