<HEAD>Chaos as Thousands Pack Venice for Pink Floyd Concert</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VENICE, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An estimated 50,000 people poured into the city of canals Saturday for a free concert by the rock group <ORGANIZATION> Pink </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Floyd </ORGANIZATION>, set to perform on a floating stage near <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mark </LOCATION>'s Square. By early Saturday morning, 12 hours before the concert was scheduled to begin, alleyways were packed and police were trying to regulate the flow of people in this city of 83,000. The situation was exacerbated by a 24-hour transport strike that caused chaos for inhabitants and tourists alike. An emergency service linking up the islands, however, was in operation. The rail authorities issued a strong warning, telling people to stay away from <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION> with the influx of rock fans exceeding all predictions. Many people spent Friday night sleeping outside the rail station or near St Mark's Square. On Saturday the square was transformed into a kind of sunbathing area as young people, wearing bikinis and swimming shorts, took advantage of the sunshine while waiting for the concert to begin. The concert was surrounded by controversy from the outset, with residents and officials concerned that the loud music could damage the city's historic buildings. Permission to go ahead with concert was only given Thursday after the British group agreed to keep the volume down and organizers agreed to move the floating stage farther from St. Mark's Square than originally planned.
