<TEXT>
 A strike by French air traffic control technicians disrupted flight schedules Saturday throughout much of <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, causing delays of up to 10 hours on some flights, officials said. Civil aviation officials at <LOCATION> Orly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> said the strike by technicians, who maintain radars and other electronic equipment used for takeoffs and landings, was scheduled to last until Monday. It began Tuesday. Controllers were ordered to increase spacing between flights as a safety measure. The domestic airline <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inter </ORGANIZATION> predicted delays on about 30 of its 240 flights Saturday, and the backups disrupted flights elsewhere in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The technicians are seeking increased staffing and changes in career promotion ladders to match those of air traffic controllers. The <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said technicians should be satisfied with results of negotiations in October, which it said resulted in an agreement giving them `` advantages comparable to those of the other categories'' of air traffic control employees. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> said French controllers had cut the number of British flights handled from 54 to a half dozen per hour, and British air traffic controllers were offering to reroute some flights. The dispute delayed British flights to <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> by up to 5 -LCB- hours. Flights to and from <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> also were affected. The Spanish flag carrier <ORGANIZATION> Iberia </ORGANIZATION> canceled 16 flights to and from <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> countries