<HEAD>Alternate Meeting Attracts Representatives of Poorest Peoples</HEAD>
<UNK>By SYDNEY RUBIN ^Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 While leaders of the world's seven richest nations met behind closed doors Saturday, representatives of the seven `` poorest peoples'' held a public meeting across town on the <LOCATION> Left </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Burkina </PERSON> <PERSON> Faso </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION> and the Brazilian <ORGANIZATION> Amazon </ORGANIZATION> were represented by doctors, poets, women's and human rights activists, labor leaders and ethnic emissaries. <PERSON> Orlando </PERSON> <PERSON> Melgueiros </PERSON> <PERSON> da </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON>, bare-chested and in a feather headdress, represented <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s Union of Indigenous Nations. The meeting of the Seven Poorest Peoples occurred under the auspices of The Other Economic Summit, an annual conference searching for alternative solutions at the same time the leaders of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> are meeting. `` We seek an alternative economic development which will do away with social injustice, the north's domination of Third World countries and the thoughtless pillage of the earth's resources,'' explained the conference paper. More than 1,000 participants attended the meeting. A final declaration issued Saturday night called for a `` radical transformation of the international political and economic system'' to make sure decisions were not taken just by the rich countries, but `` with all the peoples of the world.'' The statement also called for a ban on the use of international loans for arms purchases, for controls on `` destructive energy consumption'' and forgiveness of the debt owed by poor countries to the rich. The summit, held alongside the seven-nation economic summit, or G-7, every year since 1974, included such seminars as `` Education for the Third Millenium'' and `` Without Arms, Citizens?'' which explored the role of private citizens in the peace process and disarmament. Like the leaders across town, the alternative summiteers also discussed international debt, economics and the environment. <PERSON> Konrad </PERSON> <PERSON> Von </PERSON> <PERSON> Moltke </PERSON>, a senior fellow with the <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> and the World Wide Fund for Nature in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, prepared a background paper on the environment for the <ORGANIZATION> G-7 </ORGANIZATION> summit but dropped in at the alternative summit as well. `` In dealing with environmental problems, the relationships are no longer big and small, powerful and weak nations, because we are all interdependent,'' he said.
