<TEXT>
 Businessman <PERSON> Nestor </PERSON> <PERSON> Rapanelli </PERSON> was sworn in Saturday as the fifth economy minister in 3 -LCB- months, and he pledged to complete the austerity program of <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> Roig </PERSON>, who died only six days after taking office. <PERSON> Rapanelli </PERSON>, 60, took his oath of office from President <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> in the same Government House room where an all-night wake was held for <PERSON> Roig </PERSON>, whose death of a heart attack Friday shook the beleaguered South American nation. The new minister said he would `` continue the policies of Roig'' in an effort to halt hyperinflation, end <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s worst recession in 173 years and stop the widespread hunger that produced food riots in May. A voluntary price accord with businesses that would allow the government to coordinate wage increases `` will be signed on Monday or Tuesday,'' <PERSON> Rapanelli </PERSON> told reporters. <PERSON> Roig </PERSON>, 68, had been negotiating the agreement at the time of his death. In choosing <PERSON> Rapanelli </PERSON>, <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> turned again to the giant <ORGANIZATION> Bunge </ORGANIZATION> and Born grain conglomerate, where the new minister served as vice president, as had <PERSON> Roig </PERSON> until his retirement three years ago. <PERSON> Rapanelli </PERSON> `` is the right man to maintain our economic program,'' said <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> as he joined <PERSON> Roig </PERSON>'s family, friends and other officials at the wake. <PERSON> Rapanelli </PERSON> has worked for <ORGANIZATION> Bunge </ORGANIZATION> and Born for 39 years. He also is vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Executive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> and is a director of the <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Latin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investigation </ORGANIZATION>. He faces a formidable task in continuing the program outlined by <PERSON> Roig </PERSON>, who was sworn in July 8 following <PERSON> Menem </PERSON>'s inauguration. <PERSON> Roig </PERSON> on Sunday announced a 54 percent devaluation of the austral and raised state-controlled utility prices by at least 200 percent. The currency held firm against the dollar, which Argentines use as a hedge against inflation, during the first three days of the week. But on Thursday, the dollar's value on the black market soared above 700 australs, compared to the official rate of 650, following a series of rumors, including one that <PERSON> Roig </PERSON> might resign. Inflation grew by 114.5 percent in June and projections for July are 200 percent or more. Unemployment stands at about 10 percent. Real wages have shrunk by an estimated 60 percent. The economic crisis led to food riots in late May that claimed at least 14 lives. Thousands of Argentines now receive daily meals at soup kitchens that were set up last month. <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> has estimated that 9 million of the country's 30 million inhabitants are `` living at the edge of misery.'' On Saturday, the government sent 140 tons of food to the northern provinces of Chaco and <LOCATION> Tucuman </LOCATION> for distribution among the needy. <PERSON> Rapanelli </PERSON> is the nation's fifth economy minister since March 31, the day <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Sourrouille </PERSON> resigned after failing to stabilize the economy. Two other ministers, <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Pugliese </PERSON> and then <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON>, also failed to implement economic reforms under former President <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON>, whose <ORGANIZATION> Radical </ORGANIZ