<SECOND>AM-Dioxin Scare,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Bans Sale Of Dioxin-Tainted Milk And Meat Products</HEAD>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government has banned the sale of milk and meat products from farms near two large waste incinerators after foodstuffs from the farms were found to be contaminated by dioxin. The decision was announced in a letter to <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> late Friday and followed tests showing that the milk contained three times the amount of dioxin considered normal, according to <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Dankmeyer </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Heath </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman. The official described the measures as `` precautionary'' and said there was no immediate danger to public health. However, <PERSON> Dankmeyer </PERSON> added that consumers drinking the contaminated milk on a daily basis would ultimately take in more dioxin than is considered safe, he said. The government also ordered the waste furnaces to take stricter anti-pollution measures and was considering suing them for damages, he said. Dioxin is a highly toxic chemical contaminant that can be released into the atmosphere as a byproduct of waste combustion. It has been used in chemical warfare. At issue is the milk and meat produce of 16 dairy farms surrounding the <ORGANIZATION> Rijnmond </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Waste </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disposal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> near <LOCATION> Rotterdam </LOCATION>, the nation's largest combustion furnace for domestic waste. The annual milk output of those farms is about 1 million gallons but there was no immediate word how much of the tainted milk had been sold or over what period. The government announced similar measures for farms in the area of a waste furnace near <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION> after theoretical calculations showed the same level of dioxin pollution was likely there, <PERSON> Dankmeyer </PERSON> said. Tests on produce from the <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION> site still need to be completed, he said, adding that 10 similar combustion furnaces elsewhere in the country were believed safe. Milk from the two sites will be taken to a specially designated dairy factory, where the milkfat, in which dioxin accumulates, will be skimmed off and destroyed. The remainder will be converted into powdered milk, <PERSON> Dankmeyer </PERSON> said. Meat originating from any of the stricken farms will also be destroyed, said <PERSON> Dankmeyer </PERSON>, adding that farmers will be fully compensated.
