<HEAD>Summit, Bicentennial Draw Media Hordes to Paris</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLINE ALLEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Slung with I.D. tags and touting lenses worth more than the per capita income of poorer countries, 6,000 journalists descended on <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> to report on the summit of the world's seven richest nations and revel in the glamour of the French bicentennial celebrations. The summit and the media circus moved into the barely-completed <ORGANIZATION> Arche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION>, the glittering 35-story cube that crowns the <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> business district on <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>' western edge. Camera crews relished the panorama from the 54-step climb to the marble base of the Arche, a structure that forced writers to dust off their architectural vocabulary: the consensus settled on `` post-modernist.'' Close-mouthed about the cost, the French have splashed out the hospitality for the more than 30 heads of state and the journalists who traced their every move. Open bars and four 500-seat tented pavillions at the Arche offered 23,000 lavish meals to ravenous reporters during the summit weekend. The timing of the summit _ after President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s Eastern European tour _ and the bicentennial festivities have brought out the media stars. <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rather </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Brokaw </PERSON> all broadcast from famous Parisian sites. The festivities and the summit stretched logistics organizers to the limit. `` Each time we try to do smarter and better with less people,'' says <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Siegel </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>, which has a team of about 50 on the mission. Like other media organizations, <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> has added staff but mainly to handle the bicentennial side or the economic issues. The military parades, dance extravaganzas and the fireworks bursting over the summer crowds have provided a colorful finish to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s headline-grabbing swing through <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> network originated its Business World show from here. <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s Good Morning America also broadcast a special on the bicentennial from Notre Dame cathedral, while <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> originated Today from the Quai de Tournelle. Each of the three major networks lined up top <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> adminstration officials for its Sunday morning talk shows _ Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> on <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>, national security adviser <PERSON> Brent </PERSON> <PERSON> Scowcroft </PERSON> on <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> and White House Chief of Staff <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> on <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>. For a crew from <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION>, the two events complement each other. `` What President -LRB- <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> was trying to do involving the summit in the bicentennial makes it more festive,'' said <PERSON> Takemi </PERSON> <PERSON> Shiga </PERSON>. `` But I think if the summit was not held in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> the bicentennial would not be so much reported.'' Some reporters grumbled about the readiness of the French for the media hordes. Crews cited delayed accreditation, the half-finished state of the Arche, which lead to power cuts and communications problems, the endless security checks and the travel arrangements between assorted press centers and hotels. Reporters traveling in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> presidential motorcade got separated from the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> limousine more than once, while other groups followed the president for seven-hour stretches without even seeing him. But the White House press room, esconced in the <ORGANIZATION> Meridien </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hotel </ORGANIZATION>, has allowed journalists from other countries and non-U.S. agencies to join expanded travel pools. `` The problems we have had here are unavoidable,'' said a <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> journalist who did not want to be named. `` Things would be simpler for foreigners who spoke even a few words of French.''
