as head of state; picks up 8th graf, ``The official</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GOLDSMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Mobutu </PERSON> <PERSON> Sese </PERSON> <PERSON> Seko </PERSON> arrived to view the lavish military parade on the <LOCATION> Champs-Elysees </LOCATION> marking <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s bicentennial, they automatically strode up to the front row, befitting their place as leaders of their countries. Embarrassed French officials had to show them to their seats _ at the back of the bullet-proof stand. The seating order, the officials explained, was dictated by protocol. But how that magic formula is determined remains a mystery. The summit of the world's seven richest nations, the simultaneous meeting of some two dozen Third World leaders and the celebrations for the 200th anniversary of the French Revolution were all ruled by protocol. A <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said Saturday the seven were led by <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, the host nation, followed in order by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, Ialy and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. The spokesman said the order was determined by the years the leader had held his office. Protocol placed President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, barely six months into his term, ahead of the others because he, like <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>, is a head of state and not merely a head of government, like Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> and the rest. The official could not give any motivation for the order in which the leaders of the other 27 countries _ most of whom went home Saturday _ were ranked. Protocol was invented by the French before the French Revolution as a set of rules for the behavior of diplomats. As host, French President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> was able to use protocol to get his message across, putting emphasis where he felt it was due and, perhaps, putting world leaders such as <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> in their place. As master of ceremonies, <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> was able to control events, from how the heads of government lined up for the official photograph to the order in which they made their getaways by limousine. <PERSON> Mobutu </PERSON>, who was not invited but came anyway, is on the French government's blacklist for his checkered human rights record. Wearing his trademark leopard skin cap, <PERSON> Mobutu </PERSON> strode to the front row of every meeting, only to find he was seated inconspicuously at the back. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> was booed by the French public Friday for recalling the `` incredible terror'' of their hallowed revolution and likening it to latter day exterminations in communist lands. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> had a place of honor on <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>'s left in the formal group photo taken of the seven; <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was on his right. `` We could not do anything else, since she was the only lady among the leaders,'' a <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman explained. But at the inauguration of the new opera house at the <LOCATION> Bastille </LOCATION>, Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> found she had to take a back seat with <PERSON> Mobutu </PERSON>, while <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was in front, alongside <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON>. At Friday's military parade, the <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> prime minister was among the last allowed to leave the bulletproof enclosure encircling the leaders. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s Uno was also in the rear guard. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> and his motocycle escort left first, as is the custom for the host. But the arrangements for the others had not been made clear in advance. So, for several minutes, the leaders sat on their red velvet chairs not daring to move for fear of _ what else? _ upsetting protocol. When the order of departure was finally sorted out, President <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> <PERSON> Houphouet-Boigny </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Ivory </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, a leader of the underprivileged countries, was first out of the gate, followed swiftly by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. In the confusion, the leaders' cars got out of order and some almost collided. President <PERSON> Omar </PERSON> <PERSON> Bongo </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Gabon </LOCATION> decided to return to his hotel on foot. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> was unable to win approval of his idea for a North-South summit of the nation's rich and poor countries. But he was able to ensure that the leaders of the poor nations had plenty of opportunities to mix and mingle with the presidents and prime ministers of the mighty seven. He threw them together at every opportunity.
