<HEAD>Residents Report More Shooting in Somallia's Capital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gunfire rang through <LOCATION> Somalia </LOCATION>'s capital on Saturday for a second straight day, residents said, and police increased the death toll to 23 from clashes between security forces and religious demonstrators. Police said 59 people were wounded in Friday's clashes in <LOCATION> Somalia </LOCATION>'s capital, <LOCATION> Mogadishu </LOCATION>, when security forces opened fire on what the government termed `` troublemakers hiding behind the banner of religion.'' It was unclear what caused the violence. The government Friday gave the death toll as 10. It did not explain why the casualty count was increased Saturday. In <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> summoned the ambassador from <LOCATION> Somalia </LOCATION> on Saturday to express its concern about the lives of Italians in the country. The ministry also said a military plane had flown from <LOCATION> Mogadishu </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Nairobi </LOCATION> on Saturday with about 40 Italians who asked to leave <LOCATION> Somalia </LOCATION>. Residents, who spoke by telephone, said shots were heard periodically around the East African capital Saturday but that the shooting lacked the intensity of Friday's clashes. The residents, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the city was otherwise calm and that authorities lifted a 6 p.m-6 a.m. curfew. Somali President <PERSON> Mohamed </PERSON> <PERSON> Siad </PERSON> <PERSON> Barre </PERSON>, in a statement broadcast over state radio and monitored in <LOCATION> Nairobi </LOCATION>, offered his condolences to the relatives of victims and said the clashes were over and `` things were back to normal.'' The government said Friday that security forces opened fire after religious demonstrators attacked them with stones, knives and sticks. A resident contacted by telephone Friday said it appeared troops had opened fire as Moslem worshipers left their place of prayer. Islam is the state religion in the overwhelmingly pastoral, impoverished nation of about 9 million. Friday is normally the Moslem Sabbath, but July 14 also was the occasion for feast and celebration of the hajj, the Moslem pilgrimage to the holy city of <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION>. There were reports during the week that several Moslem religious leaders and other prominent citizens had been detained by authorities, but it was not known whether the reported arrests were related to the clashes. On July 9, a gunman killed <PERSON> Mogadishu </PERSON>'s Roman Catholic bishop, <PERSON> Salvatore </PERSON> <PERSON> Pietro </PERSON> <PERSON> Colombo </PERSON>. It was not known whether the disturbances were connected to that incident. There are an estimated 2,000 Roman Catholics in <LOCATION> Somalia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Siad </PERSON> <PERSON> Barre </PERSON>, who has ruled since 1969, has not allowed journalists to visit for more than a year. Since 1981, <LOCATION> Somalia </LOCATION> has battled the <ORGANIZATION> Somali </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION>, which demands <PERSON> Barre </PERSON>'s removal. Intensified fighting in the last 18 months has driven more than 200,000 Somalis into refugee camps in neighboring <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>.
