<SECOND>AM-Fire Center,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Season Simmers After Two Week Send-off</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK WARBIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After a frenzied two weeks to kick off the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>'s wildfire season, activity scaled back to a simmer by week's end at the federal <ORGANIZATION> Boise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interagency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> But old hands at the national command post know the slack is only a lull between storms _ a chance to sharpen shovels, restock supplies and rest before the next onslaught. High-tech sensors to detect lightning strikes offer clues, but where fires will rage is beyond even the center's experts in firefighting tactics, manpower allocation, weather forecasting and logistics. `` All we can say for sure is conditions remain hot and dry. The rest is up to <PERSON> Mother </PERSON> <PERSON> Nature </PERSON>,'' said spokesman <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartigan </PERSON>. `` We are far from being out of the fire season yet.'' The <LOCATION> Boise </LOCATION> center is the federal government's logistics and support nerve center for firefighting activities across <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. There were 33,388 fires reported nationwide to the <LOCATION> Boise </LOCATION> center through Thursday. That was well below the 56,489 reported through July 13 last year, when blazes across the northern Rockies were beginning to spread rapidly through drought-parched brush and timber. Almost 6 million acres were burned last year, including more than 1 million acres of <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION>, where flames changed the famous landscape for generations. Federal agencies spent almost $ 584 million on firefighting. This year's fires, although not as numerous, are bigger. Nationwide, they had burned almost 130,000 acres more through Thursday than the 1.1 million acres blackened by the same time in 1988. Officials say the reasons include large spring blazes in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Southwest </LOCATION>, barely accessible terrain and plentiful, well-cured fuel after a number of years without fires in this season's hot spots. The 1989 fires also are further south. The focus of fire activity last summer was <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and northern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. This year it's <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. `` It's where the drought is,'' <PERSON> Hartigan </PERSON> said. `` The pattern has shifted southwest. But I'd have to say that almost all of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>, with very few exceptions, is still not entirely recovered from four years of drought.'' As far east as <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION>, where the impact of drought is more often seen in withering corn fields, fire is taking its toll. But overall, the first assault of the 1989 fire season still pales in comparison with the memory of 1988. About 12,500 firefighters were in the field at the height of activity last week. There were about 30,000 during the first week of September last year, including 5,600 Army and Marine troops. <PERSON> Hartigan </PERSON> said the help provided by those crews, primarily at <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION>, gave fire bosses an extra tool they hope will be unnecessary this summer. `` What we learned is military troops are physically fit, they're disciplined and we can train them to do what we need to do in just a couple of days,'' he said `` We're not anticipating the need for that, but we want to be prepared.''
