<SECOND>AM-Summit-Debt,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House Raises Possibility of Breakthrough in Mexico Debt Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, test case for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>' new strategy to ease the foreign debt problem, may clinch a deal shortly with bankers to trim its $ 100 billion loan portfolio, a White House official said Saturday. `` It is in the dotting the ` i' and crossing the ` t' stage on some of the tough details that are important both of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and the banks,'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> told reporters. <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON>, President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s chief of staff, raised the possibility of an agreement by Sunday's conclusion of the economic summit of the seven major industrialized nations in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and other officials want an early end to the talks with <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> to prove the viability of its new approach on the $ 1.3 trillion debt of developing nations. The strategy, marking a sharp turn in American policy, emphasizes debt forgiveness or reduction for the poorer nations. Finance ministers taking part in the summit from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> called on commercial banks to play their part in the latest debt plan. `` We felt the banks should get on with the negotiations,'' said <LOCATION> Canadian </LOCATION> Finance Minister <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>. `` We feel the resources that are in place are adequate to do the job.'' <PERSON> Toyoo </PERSON> <PERSON> Gyoten </PERSON>, deputy Japanese finance minister, said, `` The main thrust was we have to continue to put the wind in the sails -LRB- of bankers -RRB- and keep it moving.'' In supporting the current approach, the officials turned aside fresh pleas for more help from leaders of poorer nations, who were in town to mark Friday's 200th anniversary of the French revolution. In their economic talks, summit participants were generally upbeat about the economic outlook but warned of the threat posed by rising inflation in some countries. `` There's no recession talk at all,'' said <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>. `` There's no country who saw a recession on the horizon or the possibility of a recession on the horizon.'' But, he said, `` Inflation is a problem we must continue to deal with, that we must continue to be vigilant on.'' The officials also stressed the importance of correcting the budget and trade imbalances run up by some countries. They urged countries to make sure the current round of trade liberalization end on a successful note by their scheduled 1990 deadline. The talks, under the auspices of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, have been hampered by disputes over agricultural subsidies and other issues. The 96-nation <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> is a forum and arrangement to promote free world trade. Much of the attention of the economic discussions has been focused on <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s debt negotiations. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> is the developing world's No. 2 debtor, behind <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>. It has often taken the lead in finding new ways to ease the debt load. <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON>, showing his thumb and index finger nearly touching, said <LOCATION> Mexican </LOCATION> officials and private bankers `` are now about that far apart.'' He said another bargaining session was expected `` in the next 24 hours or so. And it is hoped that at that meeting substantially most of, if not all, of that gap will be closed.'' <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> also said the debt talks were `` pretty close.'' He said a Mexican deal could `` clearly be an incentive to other countries'' to make economic changes required for participation in the rich countries' debt plan. It calls for debtor nations to cut inflation rates, strengthen their currencies and take other steps to regain their economic health. Treasury Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> said Friday the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was willing to work with the other industrialized nations to arrange a $ 1 billion to $ 2 billion emergency loan to help <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> meet its obligations while it negotiates with private bankers for a new debt accord. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> owes private lenders $ 54 billion, with about $ 15 billion due American banks. In its negotiations with bankers, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> wants to slash both its overall debt and the amount of its annual interest payments, which run about $ 10 billion a year. Both sides have tentatively agreed on a 35 percent discount that would mean savings to <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> of about $ 3 billion in annual debt payments, according to sources who demanded anonymity.
