<FIRST>u i AM-Summit-GoodIntentions 2ndLd-Writethru a0576 07-15 0699</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Summit-Good Intentions, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0576,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Summit Statement Reflects Lack of Economic or Political Peril</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs. Restores dropped AP news analysis line</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Harmony and reverence for human rights echoed Saturday from the summit document adopted by leaders of seven democracies in a windowless room on the 35th floor of the Grand Arch, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s newest national symbol. On the bicentennial of the French Revolution, it was only natural that President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and his six partners reaffirmed their commitment to freedom and democratic principles even as they pointedly urged <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> to cease its repression of pro-democracy forces. But facing no immediate threats to their security or their economies, the summiteers issued a mild communique. It thundered at terrorists without identifying their supporters. It skirted the oppressive hunger of the undernourished Third World. And it pledged no cold cash for <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> to smooth the transition of the two Soviet bloc countries to free market economies. Even before the leaders opened their deliberations Friday evening at a lavish dinner of stuffed lobster and lamb, washed down with Chateau Montrose 1918, a tentative <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> proposal to create a `` clearinghouse'' for aid to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> was jettisoned. At the last minute, West German Chancellor <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON>, working in tandem with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, won approval for a conference of `` all interested countries'' later this summer to consider <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s urgent food problems and `` concerted support for reform'' in the two countries. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> paved the way with letters to his summit partners before he came to <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. For now, Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> told reporters, the site, agenda and participants in the aid-for-Poland conference have not been determined. French President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>, a Socialist host presiding over a gathering of largely conservative leaders, found no support for his proposal to set up an international conference with poor countries to consider ways to ease their staggering $ 1.3 trillion debt. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> had to abandon the idea. With some two dozen heads of Third World countries here as bicentennial guests, the communique offered hopeful rhetoric _ but, as expected, not much else. The section on <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> called on the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> to postpone new loans as a way of registering `` our deep sense of condemnation'' over <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s repressive measures. Also, Chinese students apprehensive about returning home were assured they could stay indefinitely in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. No sanctions were recommended, an apparent ratification of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s policy of taking a measured approach to events in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said the President had taken the lead on the subject at the summit. `` We look to the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> authorities to create conditions which will avoid their isolation and provide for a return to cooperation based upon the resumption of movement towards political and economic reform and openness,'' the communique said with a diplomatic lack of directness. And while the seven leaders encouraged `` greater freedom and democracy'' in Central and <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, they evinced no sign of fervor or immediate aid to match <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> incentives of $ 115 million and $ 25 million that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> extended to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> during his visits there. Even so, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> was pleased with the overall results. He said the leaders got along so well they may be able to conclude their deliberations ahead of schedule on Sunday. Having attended nine summits as White House chief of staff, <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> secretary and now secretary of <ORGANIZATION> state </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said this was `` the most harmonious and one of the most productive summits that I have attended.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, after breakfast Saturday with <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>, dismissed the absence of specific aid commitments from his summit partners. `` There have been some misconceptions we would come in here with a dollar package,'' the president said. `` I managed to convey in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> that that was not the case and here it is not the case.'' He said the communique `` vindicated'' his approach. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> said, meanwhile, `` We are all very anxious to help. We are all helping, each in our own way.''
