<HEAD>OAS, In Third Mediation Effort, Pulls Military Into Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Mediators from the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> States </ORGANIZATION> said Saturday that the government and opposition leaders have agreed to hold talks to resolve <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s political crisis. A statement by the mission from the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> States </ORGANIZATION> said the talks were scheduled to begin Sunday `` without an agenda, without preconditions and with the commitment that no topic would be excluded.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> will send representatives to the talks as part of the government delegation, the statement said. The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> chief, Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, is the nation's de factor leader and is under pressure to quit. Up to now, the position of the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> and the government has been that <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s situation was not subject to discussion. Saturday's announcement `` that no topic would be excluded'' seemed to indicate a change of attitude. It will be the first time that the Defense Forces, government and opposition have held talks. The <ORGANIZATION> OAS </ORGANIZATION> delegation arrived Saturday on its third mediation visit since <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s regime annulled an election May 7 that international observers say opposition candidates won by a landslide. <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>'s Foreign Minister <PERSON> Diego </PERSON> <PERSON> Cordovez </PERSON> is heading the mission, which includes foreign ministers <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Palencia </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Sadeo </PERSON> <PERSON> Badseo </PERSON> of Trinidad-Tobago, and <ORGANIZATION> OAS </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-General <PERSON> Joao </PERSON> <PERSON> Baena </PERSON> <PERSON> Soares </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>. Opposition presidential candidate <PERSON> Guillermo </PERSON> <PERSON> Endara </PERSON>, backed by a coalition of his own <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, is demanding <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s ouster and that the government admit it lost the election. The opposition also accuses <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> of human rights violations, corruption and press censorship. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> has been under pressure from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to step down since two federal grand juries indicted him in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> in February 1988 on drug trafficking and money-laundering charges. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> has accused the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> of trying replace him with a docile government that would agree to a continuation of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military presence beyond Dec. 31, 1999, when the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION> is to be turned over to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>.
