<HEAD>Leftist Guerrillas Disable State Mine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Leftist guerrillas attacked one of the largest state-owned mines in the country, destroying machinery and forcing suspension of operations for six months, police said Saturday. Two mine workers were reported wounded. About 100 guerrillas from the leftist <ORGANIZATION> Shining </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Path </ORGANIZATION> group attacked the <ORGANIZATION> Morococha </ORGANIZATION> mine Friday, setting off dynamite that destroyed mining machinery, fuel tanks, electrical generators and electronic control panels, police said. The mine, owned by the state mining company Centromin-Peru, produces copper, lead, zinc and silver. It is located in the <LOCATION> Andean </LOCATION> highlands 70 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION> at more than 13,000 feet above sea level in the department of <LOCATION> Junin </LOCATION>. Police in <LOCATION> Huancayo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Junin </LOCATION>'s capital, said the guerrillas first attacked the police station of <ORGANIZATION> Morococha </ORGANIZATION> with dynamite to prevent officers from reaching the mine. Two mine workers who tried to repel the attack on the mine were seriously wounded, the police said. Centromin-Peru employs about 17,000 miners, 3,000 of them at the <ORGANIZATION> Morococha </ORGANIZATION> mine. The company brings in about $ 300 million a year to this impoverished nation. The Shining Path has been battling <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s elected government since 1980. The government says more than 15,000 people have died in the war. Mining companies have been asking officials for more protection against terrorist attacks. Rebel groups often target the isolated mining camps to hinder production and steal dynamite, food and medicine.
