<HEAD>Weather Reports to Include Sunburn Index</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICE GRAVINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Weather forecasts here will have something new beginning this week _ the `` scorch factor,'' which two local physicians hope will remind folks of the dangers of skin cancer. With a shoebox-size device on the roof of a <ORGANIZATION> Baylor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> building, <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Menter </PERSON> and <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> can calculate how long it will take the sun's ultraviolet rays to start burning unprotected skin. The physicians have begun reporting to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> ultraviolet readings at 10 a.m., noon and 3 p.m., along with the number of minutes a sun-sensitive person can be exposed without harm. One <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> television station will add the roast quotient to its evening weather reports starting Monday, and several other TV and radio stations have expressed interest in the index. Similar reports are available through the weather service in <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> said. `` We're trying to make people aware that there is a sun out there that is doing damage to their skin,'' said <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>, a medical center internist who is switching to dermatology. <PERSON> Menter </PERSON>, a dermatologist, is medical director of the <ORGANIZATION> Baylor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Psoriasis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> has one of the highest rates of skin cancer in the country, <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> said. `` Of course, we're in the sun belt, and in the south you get more ultraviolet exposure,'' he said. `` And because of the weather, people tend to develop more of an outdoor lifestyle. So skin cancer is a real problem.'' He added that certain types of skin cancer can be fatal if not treated early, and sun damage can also hasten the aging of the skin. People who stay outside longer than the index suggests _ usually 15 to 30 minutes on a sunny or partly-cloudy day _ should cover up or apply sun screens, <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> said. He added that weather can fool people. `` They equate heat with sunburn, so they think August is going to be the peak'' in ultraviolet radiation, he said. In fact, the ultraviolet rays peak in June and July, then decline steadly to late December, when the sun is farthest away from the <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hemisphere </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> said.
