<HEAD>Biggest Atom Smasher Starts Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY CZUCZKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Reseachers have successfully made the first test run of the world's biggest atom smasher, a 17-mile circular tunnel designed to unlock secrets of how the universe took shape, scientists said Saturday. On Friday evening, scientists at the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Particle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Physics </ORGANIZATION> outside the capital sent a first beam of particles around the new particle accelerator, known as the Large Electron-Positron Collider or LEP. The $ 790 million machine, built underground beneath the <LOCATION> French-Swiss </LOCATION> border, is expected to put the European lab ahead of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> rivals in the search for new discoveries in high-energy physics, although plans are in the works for a 53-mile super collider in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Carlo </PERSON> <PERSON> Rubbia </PERSON>, an Italian physics professor and Nobel laureate who heads the lab, cheered along with other scientists in the control room as instruments showed a positron beam completed its course in 50 minutes, said lab spokesman <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Calder </PERSON> said. A positron is a positively charged antiparticle of an electron. `` This simply means that all parts of the machine, all the magnets, are correctly positioned,'' said the spokesman for the lab outside <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, known by the French acronym <ORGANIZATION> CERN </ORGANIZATION>. The collider, built over eight years with funding from <ORGANIZATION> CERN </ORGANIZATION>'s 14 member states, is the most powerful particle accelerator and the largest scientific instrument ever made. <PERSON> Rubbia </PERSON> says it should `` guarantee <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> a dominant position in particle physics for many years to come.'' The <ORGANIZATION> LEP </ORGANIZATION> will recreate with new sophistication the wild swirl of matter just after the so-called big bang, the explosion many scientists believe created the universe up to 20 billion years ago. The three-mile <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Linear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Collider </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Menlo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, in April won the race to produce the first so-called Z particles, which scientists say could have existed naturally for only an instant after a big bang. But the <ORGANIZATION> CERN </ORGANIZATION> machine is expected to produce thousands of Z particles by September, opening a greater scope for discovery. Watching Z particles decay into other particles is expected to yield new clues to the structure of matter and the development of the universe. <PERSON> Rubbia </PERSON> shared the 1984 Physics Nobel Prize with Dutch scientist <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> der </PERSON> <PERSON> Meer </PERSON> for discovering the Z particle in an old particle accelerator at <ORGANIZATION> CERN </ORGANIZATION>, but stronger colliders are needed to make enough particles to allow scientists to draw conclusions. Z particles have also been produced at the <ORGANIZATION> Fermi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accelerator </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> near <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. That four-mile track was the biggest accelerator in the world until the new <ORGANIZATION> CERN </ORGANIZATION> machine was built.
