<HEAD>Mitterrand Takes Summiteers To Tour His Project</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT J. WIELAARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 French President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> on Saturday gave the summit leaders a personal guided tour of his pet project _ 12th century ruins discovered beneath the <LOCATION> Louvre </LOCATION>. After their first full day of talks came to an end under the Pyramid, the avant-garde glass structure that sits in the <LOCATION> Louvre </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON> <PERSON> Courtyard </PERSON>, <PERSON> Mitterand </PERSON> guided his guests from the underground meeting site and into the excavated ruins under the museum The 8-meter-high moat walls and guard towers are all that remains of the castle fortress of French King Philippe-Auguste. Construction of the Louvre was begun in the 16th century on top of the medieval fortress, of which only an 80-square-meter section survives. The relic of medieval <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> is dear to <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>'s heart, officials said, because it was only discovered during the excavations to build the complex underneath the architecturally controversial Pyramid. Both <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> and his culture minister, <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Lang </PERSON>, were roundly criticized for plunking down the gleaming glass Pyramid in the <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON> <PERSON> Courtyard </PERSON> of the austere U-shaped Louvre, the world's largest royal palace, and now one of the world's most famous museums `` Mr. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> loves this place,'' said <PERSON> Evelyne </PERSON> <PERSON> Richard </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the French president. `` The construction of the pyramid began in 1983, and the works were delayed because of this find.'' While <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> led the way down a subterranean boardwalk in the dry moat bed, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s director of museums, <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Laclotte </PERSON>, explained the history of the fortress to West German Chancellor <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON>, President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Prime Ministers <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Suosuke </PERSON> <PERSON> Uno </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Ciriaco </PERSON> <PERSON> Mita </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>, his guests, and their interpreters then crowded into a dimly lit antechamber where there is a display of artifacts discovered during the excavation. A cacophony of languages echoed off the concrete walls as the translators struggled to keep pace with <PERSON> Laclotte </PERSON>'s explanations, and the Western leaders asked questions. Among the finds were a golden fragment of the crown of the late medieval King <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> VI </PERSON>. After the tour, <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> led his guests into the Louvre for champagne and hors d'oeuvres, as the setting sun streamed through the windows of the palace on the Seine. The setting for the cocktail session was a recently opened gallery of Greek and Roman statuary, which the summit leaders toured as they chatted.
