<BYLINE>By PHILLIP RAWLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Twenty years after man walked on the moon, those responsible for that `` one giant leap for mankind'' said the space program needs another bold challenge to recapture <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s imagination. And with <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s imagination, they said, will come the financial support needed for a daring project, such as landing astronauts on <LOCATION> Mars </LOCATION>. On Saturday, a soldout crowd of more than 4,000 people joined the Apollo 11 crew _ <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON>, <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> `` Buzz'' <PERSON> Aldrin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> _ at the <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Space </LOCATION> and Rocket Center for the first of four celebrations around the country to commemorate the lunar landing on July 20, 1969. <LOCATION> Huntsville </LOCATION>'s celebration focuses on the role this northern <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> city and the <PERSON> Wernher </PERSON> <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Braun </PERSON> rocket team at <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Marshall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Flight </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> played in developing the Saturn V rocket to propel Apollo 11 on its journey to the moon The celebration was like a high-tech rock concert without the music. Lasers bounced off rockets exhibited throughout the center, sound effects simulated the takeoff of the Saturn V rocket to the moon, and actors portrayed <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON>'s and <PERSON> Aldrin </PERSON>'s walk on the rugged lunar landscape four days after blasting off from Kennedy Space Center. It climaxed with the Apollo 11 crew rising from a cloud of smoke 20 feet into the air to the front of a giant movie screen showing footage of their travels. The crew was surrounded by a cacophony of fireworks and dozens of dancing laser beams. <PERSON> Aldrin </PERSON>, who spent much of his time in <LOCATION> Huntsville </LOCATION> autographing his new book `` Men from <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>,'' describes the 20th anniversary as `` bittersweet.'' That's because he worries that <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> `` will sink to second-rate status'' in space if it continues on its present course. The 59-year-old former astronaut said Saturday he hoped the anniversary would help <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> set well-defined space objectives instead of having each space shuttle flight `` being an entity into itself.'' `` There is an excitement about the past but there is not an awareness of where we want to go,'' he said in an interview. He envisions the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> working with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> on space research projects, with a goal of developing spaceships that will take advantage of planetary movements to slingshot between <LOCATION> Mars </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> on five-month cycles. <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>, 58, also called for greater direction in the space program. `` One of these days, and I hope it's not too long, this country is going to decide it wants to go to Mars,'' he told a gathering of engineers who worked on the Apollo project. <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON>, 58, told the same group, `` A machine is man-made and hence imperfect. No one has ever made a perfect machine. Those of you who made the <ORGANIZATION> Saturn </ORGANIZATION> V came about as close as history ever recorded.'' <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, director at <ORGANIZATION> Marshall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Flight </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Huntsville </LOCATION> and a former member of the von <PERSON> Braun </PERSON> team, vividly remembers President <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s seemingly impossible challenge to land a man on the moon by the end of the 1960s. No president has issued an equally bold challenge since then, but he hopes President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will in a 20th anniversary speech Thursday. `` We must continue what <PERSON> Wernher </PERSON> <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Braun </PERSON> and Apollo 11 started many years ago, that is to reach out and touch another world,'' he said. `` This time our launching pad is going to be the space station.'' <PERSON> Konrad </PERSON> <PERSON> Dannenberg </PERSON>, a German rocket scientist who came to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> with <PERSON> Von </PERSON> <PERSON> Braun </PERSON> after World War II and later supervised engineering and testing of the Saturn rocket, said the moon landing `` was the biggest step for mankind that has ever taken place. I hope this -LRB- anniversary -RRB- is the first step toward an even bigger achievement.'' <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Buckbee </PERSON>, director of the Space and Rocket Center, a tourist attraction focused on space achievements, and a former member of <PERSON> Von </PERSON> <PERSON> Braun </PERSON>'s staff, said he hopes `` President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> gives us a goal. I've heard everything from a moon colony to a man on <LOCATION> Mars </LOCATION>, with a space plane in there. <PERSON> Buckbee </PERSON> said he sees only one way for <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> to recapture <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s imagination and pocketbook `` It's got to be a man on Mars landing,'' he said. `` I do n't think a space station is going to capture <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> imagination It's got to be something that puts man and machine against the hazards of space.
