<HEAD>From BAT to Batman: Billions and Billions in Deals</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf pvs to UPDATE with Paramount appeal; PICKS UP
8th graf pvs, `In Britain...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 BAT and <PERSON> Batman </PERSON> were at the center of two multibillion-dollar takeover deals that took shape on opposite sides of the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION>, one in the City of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and the other in <LOCATION> Gotham </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. Overseas, a group led by British raider Sir <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldsmith </PERSON> made a $ 21.2 billion debt-financed hostile foray for <ORGANIZATION> BAT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, a conglomerate that owns the swank <ORGANIZATION> Saks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fifth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Avenue </ORGANIZATION> chain and makes Kool cigarettes. The offer, which affirms the migration of the American big buyout to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, would amount to the second-largest deal in history behind the $ 25 billion debt-financed takeover of <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> earlier this year. But if the recent history of American hostile takeovers is any indication, this deal will go the way of all others: to court. That's where the protracted tussle over the future of New York-based giants <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> is mired, and a judge on Friday helped clear some of the sludge. Ruling on the side of <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION>'s friendly $ 14 billion offer for <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> _ the entertainment empire reaping big profits from its `` Batman'' film hit _ <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> Chancery Court Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> scuttled for now <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>'s hostile $ 12.2 billion offer for Time. The judge refused to block Time's $ 70-a-share offer. Paramount, though, appealed the ruling to the <ORGANIZATION> state </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, where all three companies are incorporated. In <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, BAT and its pursuer, a trio of powerful investors led by <PERSON> Goldsmith </PERSON>, were lining up attorneys for what promises to be a legal extravaganza. Since many BAT subsidiaries are American, the takeover could be decided in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> courts. Earlier this year, a federal judge effectively ended South Africa-controlled <ORGANIZATION> Minorco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> SA </ORGANIZATION>'s bid for <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Consolidated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gold </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fields </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> by issuing a retraining order against the acquisition. Besides highly paid investment bankers, the BAT offering would bring two other popular American financial tools to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>: the use of high-yield junk bonds and the dismemberment of a large company. No caped crusader he, <PERSON> Goldsmith </PERSON> says he wants to bust up BAT by selling its non-tobacco interests, which account for about 60 percent of its annual revenue of $ 28.7 billion. In <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, those interests include <ORGANIZATION> Saks </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Marshall </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Field </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Appleton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Papers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, one of the nation's largest insurers. While the takeover gulf between <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> appears to be narrowing, there's no denying the enormous economic gap between East and West reflected in the BAT and Time capers. As the two deals went their respective routes _ Time in court, BAT heading there _ President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was behind the Iron Curtain offering <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> $ 100 million in aid, a figure that probably wo n't approach the fees for lawyers and investment bankers in the takeover bids In other business news this week: _ One of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s commodities exchanges was back in the public eye but the reason was soybeans, not <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> surveillance The <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> issued an emergency order to curb trading in soybean futures contracts amid rumors an Italian company was trying to corner the market. A federal judge upheld the order but the Italians said they will sue to recover losses. _ More evidence emerged that the economy is contracting Wholesale prices fell 0.1 percent in June, the first drop in 18 months, retail sales fell for the second straight month and the operating rate for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> factories declined, government reports showed. _ Leaders of the world's seven richest democracies gathered in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> during the bicentennial of the French Revolution for their annual economic summit President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> won one victory in a trade dispute but was thwarted in an attempt to engineer a deal to lower <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s debt.
